<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Reshuffles Police Leaderships After Tourist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's newly-appointed
Interior Minister Habib al Adli today made massive changes in the
top posts of his ministry and the police, the Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle came as part of efforts to beef up the country's
security system after the horrific slaughter of 58 foreign
tourists on Monday in Luxor, about 500 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Adli, after taking the oath Tuesday night, transferred the
Luxor security chief, his assistant and investigation officials in
the Luxor directorate from their posts. The personnel changes
included 17 major generals, a brigadier and three colonels.
</P>
<P>
Three of the former interior minister's assistants have been
transferred in the shake-up.
</P>
<P>
President Hosni Mubarak appointed Adli after the country's
shock over security laxity that led to Monday's terrorist attack
when six gunmen opened fire on the tourists in front of the
4,500-year-old temple of Hatshepsut.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri today ordered the
closure of Aswan-Abu Simbel road to all tourist buses as part of
new security arrangement to protect tourists against any possible
threat.
</P>
<P>
Tourists wishing to visit Abu Simbel Temple will have to go
there by plane. The temple and thousands of Pharaonic tombs in
Luxor have been the hottest items on the agenda of most foreign
tourists.
</P>
<P>
The massacre, the deadliest attack in five years of Islamic
rebellion, is a blow to Egyptian efforts to encourage tourism
which sustains the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of travelers have fled the country and travel agents
worldwide canceled thousands of bookings of visits to Egypt after
the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
