<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Banks Should Re-Focus Functions: Finnish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Governor of the Bank of
Finland, Sirkka Hamalainen today stressed the need for central
banks to re-focus their functions in order to meet the current
global economic changes and liberalisation of financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Sirkka hamalainen made the remarks at a graduation ceremony
here at the Macro-Economic and Financial Management Institute of
Eastern and Southern Africa (MEFMI).
</P>
<P>
She said it is inevitable that central banks have to
relinquish some of their responsibilities in view of these
changes.
</P>
<P>
The role of central banks, she said, is shifting from that of
institutions which command and regulate markets to partners
influencing the direction of economies.
</P>
<P>
She said: ''We must be able to accommodate change and learn to
manage it.''
</P>
<P>
''The way to security is to make learning professional skills
are inevitable,permanent responsibilities,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
Eight graduates from Lesotho, Uganda, Zambia, Zimbabwe and
Malawi underwent specialised training in debt and foreign
exchange reserves management in the institute.
</P>
<P>
The Harare-based MEFMI was formed in 1994 with the main
objective to strengthen the capacity for macro-economic and
financial management by the governments of the member states. It
also aims to develop a pool of regional experts who can be relied
upon to offer their services to member countries and
international agencies.
</P>
<P>
The institute is made up of Angola, Lesotho, Malawi, Namibia,
Swaziland, Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe, with Botswana
and Kenya expected to join soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
