<HEADLINE> Pakistan Passing Through "Very Difficult Period": PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif said this evening that "the country is passing
through a very difficult period. The situation is very
deplorable."
</P>
<P>
Talking to the media at the Parliament House after postponing
his scheduled address to the nation, Sharif said that every minute
of the five-year term of his government is being wasted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the ongoing government-judiciary tussle, the prime
minister said, "We are trying to solve this situation."
</P>
<P>
Sharif noted that a case of contempt of the court has been
filed against him. "We want to have the right to appeal against
any decision" by the Supreme Court, he said.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly and the Senate adopted the amended
contempt law, tending to give protection to the prime minister in
the ongoing case of contempt against him in the apex court.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said the bill has now been forwarded to the president
for consent. "If the president gives his consent to the bill, the
situation will be resolved quickly," said Sharif.
</P>
<P>
He also said that due to the government-judiciary tussle, the
economic situation is getting worse every day. "We are at the
crossroads. The Parliament is at the crossroads," the prime
minister added.
</P>
<P>
According to informed sources this evening, Chief of the Army
Staff General Jahangir Karamat called on Sharif at the Prime
Minister's House and discussed with him the current political
situation in the country with special reference to the relations
between the government and the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Karamat returned home this morning from London, cutting short
his overseas visit in view of the prevailing political situation
in the country. He later had a meeting with President Farooq
Leghari.
</P>
<P>
Details of the meetings among the troika are not immediately
available.  
</P>
</TEXT>
