<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moussa Warns Israel Not to Butt in Iraqi-UN Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister Amr Moussa has
warned Israel not to thrust itself into the current Iraqi crisis
with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the press today, Moussa said Israel had
better "steer clear of an issue that does not concern it" and that
any Israeli involvement in the matter would only stymie any
forthcoming solution.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the current U.N.-Iraq standoff over arms
inspection. The U.S. is beefing up its military presence in the
Gulf for a possible strike on Baghdad which has expelled American
U.N. officials in charge of scuttling weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
His words came amid fear that the Gulf standoff would develop
into military hostilities between Iraq and Israel, a close
U.S. ally. Iraq opposes the peace treaties between the Arabs and
Israelis and calls for destruction of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Asserting that intensive diplomatic efforts were being exerted
to come up with a political solution to defuse the crisis, Moussa
said Egypt is making contacts with all parties concerned to
assist towards such a solution.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the Iraq-U.N. standoff will be taken up during Iraqi
Deputy Premier Tariq Aziz's visit to Egypt whose date will be set
within hours.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, scheduled to meet with Moussa and Arab League Secretary
General Esmat Abdel Meguid, has reportedly devised a proposal with
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeniv Primakov to avert a military
confrontation with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Aziz's visit to Egypt comes within the context of an Arab tour
including Libya, Tunisia, Algeria and Morocco to expound Iraq's
views on the recent tension between Iraq and the U.N..
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been contacting with Baghdad in a bid to resolve the
crisis as a skeleton crew of inspectors pulled out of Iraq
following the expulsion of the American members.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has sent two messages to Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein, urging him to comply with the U.N. resolutions and
restraining from military showdown with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
U.N. weapons inspectors pulled out of Baghdad on last Friday as
world leaders tried to resolve the 22-day-old U.N.-Iraq standoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
