<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Officials Sign Anti-corruption Pledge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Transparency International
Zimbabwe (TIZ), an organization that seeks to expose and help
curb corruption, today committed itself to an integrity pledge to
lead a campaign to instill honesty and accountability in the
society.
</P>
<P>
Participants drawn from a broad spectrum of Zimbabwean society
attended a three-day workshop, organized by TIZ and sponsored by
the European Union. They invited all political leaders, members
of parliament, local government councillors, traditional leaders
and senior public officials to add their own names to the
Zimbabwe integrity pledge.
</P>
<P>
They said corruption in low and high places attacked
development and contributed to unacceptable levels of poverty,
threatening the stability of the nation.
</P>
<P>
Signatories to the pledge will bind themselves to act
honestly, openly and with the utmost integrity in all aspects of
their lives.
</P>
<P>
"We will always put the well-being of the people of Zimbabwe
ahead of our personal interests and will use any opportunities we
may have to fight corruption," says the pledge.
</P>
<P>
Anyone signing the pledge will have to undertake that they
will voluntarily, publicly and regularly make full disclosure of
their assets and other interests and those of their immediate
families, it said.
</P>
<P>
Political parties and electoral candidates are asked to also
develop their own integrity pledges and to publicize them widely.
</P>
<P>
The participants who include representatives of civil society,
parliament, churches, judiciary, academics, government and the
private sector, pledged to combat with courage, dignity and
tolerance what they termed as a culture of fear that was
pervasive in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The participants also called for the reform of the Zimbabwe
constitution to create and support a legal framework conducive to
transparency and accountability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
