<HEADLINE> Six Killed in S. African Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Six people were killed
and one wounded when a South African light aircraft crashed into
the sea off Mozambican coast on Tuesday, the South African Civil
Aviation Authorities (CAA) said today.
</P>
<P>
One survivor sustained slight injuries and was flown back to
South Africa where he was admitted to a Johannesburg hospital,
according to a report of the South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
The nationalities of the passengers were not known.
</P>
<P>
CAA Chief Director, Rennie van Zyl, said the aircraft was
initially trapped under about four meters of water near the town
of Vilanculos.
</P>
<P>
The two-engine aircraft left for the Mozambican capital of
Maputo on Sunday en route to Vilanculos, a southern Mozambican
coastal town.
</P>
<P>
It encountered a heavy thunderstorm at Vilanculos and was
unable to land, van Zyl said.
</P>
<P>
The pilot had had radio contact with air traffic controllers
at Vilanculos shortly before the crash.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know if the pilot decided to turn back, or what
happened," van Zyl said.
</P>
<P>
He said the accident was being investigated by the Mozambican
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The CAA hoped to take part in the probe, and an inspector was
expected to arrive at the scene on Thursday, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
