<HEADLINE> UK Orders 6 Harrier Jets to Join Aircraft Carrier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Britain today stepped up its
military pressure on Iraq by ordering six Harrier jump jets to
join its aircraft carrier Invincible which is due to arrive in the
British colony of Gibraltar later tonight.
</P>
<P>
British Defense Secretary George Robertson said in a statement:
"It is a sensible precautionary measure which will help keep all
our options open."
</P>
<P>
"Saddam Hussein must understand he must fully comply with
United Nations Security Council resolutions and allow UNSCOM
inspectors back into Iraq to carry out their work without
interference," Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, Britain put a squadron of RAF Harrier jets
on a 48-hour alert and sent its aircraft carrier Invincible to
Gibralter from the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
However, no decision has been taken yet to deploy the aircraft
carrier in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Although Britain is keeping its military options open, it also
vowed to maintain diplomatic pressure on Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein as Robertson said "we will continue all diplomatic
measures to get Saddam to see sense".
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in a
statement that he would hold talks with his U.S., Russian and
French counterparts over the Iraq crisis in Geneva early on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We shall continue our work for a political agreement which
will secure our common objective: the return of the UNSCOM team to
Iraq and full compliance by Iraq with the UN resolutions," Cook
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
