<HEADLINE> Carter: No Allies Support U.S. Military Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The United States would
make mistakes if it takes unilateral military action against Iraq
and it would not win any support from its allies for that,former
President Jimmy Carter said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I think it would be a serious mistake. We would not have the
support from any of our allies if we did that. We would stand
alone if we launched a military attack," Carter told NBC in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
The ex-president said he believed the crisis, triggered by
Iraq's decision to kick American weapons inspectors out late last
month, could be resolved diplomatically and said world leaders
needed to convince the Iraqi people that U.N. sanctions would be
lifted if Baghdad complied.
</P>
<P>
He praised the role of France and Russia in trying to end the
standoff, saying "I think the United States is doing the right
thing by letting the French and the Russians try to work out some
resolution to this." 
</P>
</TEXT>
