<HEADLINE> German Money Supply Growth within Target Range </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Germany's money supply dropped to
an annualized growth rate of 5.1 percent in October compared with
5.2 percent in September, the German central bank announced today.
</P>
<P>
The latest figure indicated that the M3 money supply, the broad
measure of money circulating in the economy, was still well within
the central bank's target growth range of 3.5 percent to 6.5
percent, as was the case in the past four months.
</P>
<P>
The M3 supply serves as one of the central bank's key indicator
of the country's inflation trends, which could influence its
decisions on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in M3 growth in October reflected a reduction in
bank leadings to the private sector, the German central bank said
today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
