<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Publishes New Brochure to Gauge EMU Implementation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Though a fully-functioning
single market is of crucial importance for growth, competitiveness
and employment, one out of four single market measures are found
not yet applied in all the 15 European Union member states.
</P>
<P>
It was pronounced today by the inaugural issue of the European
Union brochure, "Single Market Scoreboard".
</P>
<P>
The brochure, a six-monthly publication, said that the overall
rate of non-implementation of single market measures range from 3
percent in Denmark to 10 percent in Austria.
</P>
<P>
The European Union publishes the brochure to offer a picture of
the current state of the single market and to help gauge the
degree to which member states, the European Union's Council of
Ministers and the European Commission are meeting the targets laid
down in the action plan endorsed at the Amsterdam summit this past
June.
</P>
<P>
The public and businesses need to be kept informed, the
brochure said.
</P>
<P>
One of the strategic target of the action plan is to make the
existing rules more effective.
</P>
<P>
But there is still a long way to go toward the target of having
all agreed-upon single market measures correctly transposed into
national laws among the union member states.
</P>
<P>
As of November 1, the Single Market Scoreboard said, no less
than 359 single market directives have not been implemented by all
member states despite the fact that the common objective of the
European Commission and the member states is to realize the full
potential of the single market in advance of the third stage of
the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
At the Amsterdam summit, the council underlined the crucial
importance of the timely and correct transposition of all agreed
legislation into national laws.
</P>
<P>
Alongside each edition of the scoreboard brochure, the European
Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation union, also
presents a single market survey and sectoral report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
