<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Electronic Wallets to Be Introduced in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- South African bank
giants, Standard Bank and the ABSA Group, launched today an
on-line point of sale payment system, the Maestro debit card.
</P>
<P>
It will be a giant leap forward in a bid to make South Africa
one of the most advanced consumer and financial markets in the
world, senior executives of the New York-based MasterCard
International said.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the Maestro card, the first global debit
product available in South Africa, will bring immediate worldwide
purchasing power to an estimated nine million banks clients, few
of whom have payment alternatives other than cash.
</P>
<P>
The new card features easy access, high degree of safety and
privacy, said Henry Mundt, Executive Vice President of MasterCard
International.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest mass electronic empowerment ever in South
Africa, where only 5.3 percent of the population has access to
credit.
</P>
<P>
The Maestro logo on an Automatic Teller Machine (ATM) card
allows a cardholder to make purchases using the funds in their
deposit account.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of debit marks the first phase of a banking
revolution in South Africa, and is part of MasterCards's
longer-term electronic payment strategy for this market, the
executives said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
