<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Regrets U.S. No Decision on Payment of UN Arrears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Union today
strongly deplored the fact that the United States congress had
suspended its Autumn session without adopting any legislation
concerning the payment of its arrears to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union also regretted the fact that the United
States, the largest contributor and also the largest debtor to the
UN, was not signifying any intention to start settling its debts.
</P>
<P>
"It is very worrying that one of the major member states
continues not to fulfil its responsibilities under the UN charter,
which fall within its commitments under international law," said a
European Union statement.
</P>
<P>
The absence of any decision by the U.S. congress on the payment
of arrears came at a time when the UN is making an unprecedented
effort to reform its structures and methods of operation, the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the U.S. is continuing not to pay the arrears in
contribution it owes perpetuates the serious financial crisis with
which the UN is struggling and seriously affects the climate of
trust within the organization," it said.
</P>
<P>
The 15 European Union member states combine to contribute 35.4
percent of the UN's regular budget and 37.9 percent of the UN's
peace-keeping operation budgets.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, the statement said, is counting on all UN
member states to honor their obligations in full, unconditionally
and in accordance with the scale of quotas adopted by the UN
General Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
