<HEADLINE> S. African Deputy President to Visit Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Britain
will soon discuss greater economic cooperation and British
support for South Africa's ongoing negotiations for a trade
agreement with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
These topics will top the agenda when South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki meets British Prime Minister Tony Blair in
London next week.
</P>
<P>
"The overall purpose of the visit is the promotion and
consolidation of trade and investment," the South African Press
Association quoted Mbeki's spokesman Thami Ntenteni as saying
today.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, accompanied by Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin,
will leave for Britain on Monday to have a series of meetings
with British government leaders.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, he will hold talks with Blair and Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, and will also pay a courtesy call on Queen
Elizabeth II, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the two sides will sign an exchange control
protocol to complement a 1994 bilateral agreement on the
promotion and protection of trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also hold round-table discussions, presided
over by Blair and Mbeki, aimed at consolidating relations and
looking into areas of cooperation, Ntenteni said.
</P>
<P>
With Britain set to assume the presidency of the EU in January
next year, South Africa will try and muster British support for
its tough free trade agreement negotiations with the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
