<HEADLINE> Cyprus Supports Peaceful Solution of Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus said it believes that
the present crisis in Iraq over U.N. arms inspection should be
solved through diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
The position was stated here today by government spokesman
Manolis Christofides at his daily press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been escalating in the Gulf since Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein expelled Americans working with U.N. weapons
inspection teams from the country last week.
</P>
<P>
"Cyprus believes all diplomatic means for a peaceful
settlement to the problem should be exhausted," Christofides told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time Iraq should comply with U.N. Security
Council resolutions," he added.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said the Cypriot government's longstanding
position was and remains that all U.N. member states should
conform with and implement Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that member states must abide by their
obligations as outlined in the U.N. Charter and international
law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
