<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pak Govt-Judiciary Tussle Intensifies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Uncertainty rules Pakistan's
National Assembly as the three-month-long government-judiciary
confrontation intensifies.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has postponed his planned televised
address to the nation for the second time in two days.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was scheduled to address the nation at the
National Assembly at 22:00 Tuesday, but it was canceled three
hours before the scheduled time.
</P>
<P>
The planned speech was then rescheduled for 19:15 Wednesday.
However, it was again postponed. No specific date or time has been
announced by the government.
</P>
<P>
The tussle between the executive and the judiciary which began
in mid- August seemed to have ended recently with Prime Minister
Sharif finally accepting all the recommendations of Chief Justice
of the Supreme Court Sajjad Ali Shah pertaining to the elevation
of five judges to the apex court.
</P>
<P>
However, the confrontation is far from over. A case of contempt
of the court was filed against the prime minister in the first
week of November.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sharif was summoned by the Supreme Court to
appear in person Monday to justify himself as to why a contempt of
court action should not be taken against him.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is Pakistan's first prime minister to be summoned to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Then, the Parliament passed an amendment to the Contempt Act of
1976, adding a provision to file a review petition on a judgment
given in the contempt case.
</P>
<P>
The Bill, which was passed by the National Assembly in the
small hours of Tuesday and was later approved by the Senate, is
actually intended to provide protection to the prime minister and
other members of the Treasury Benches from the ill-effect of a
possible adverse judgment of the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The Bill is sent to President Farooq Leghari for consent for
which the president has 30 days to do so.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sharif urged the president to sign the amended
Bill to end the prevailing political crisis. "Earlier the Bill is
signed, sooner the crisis will come to an end," Sharif told the
media at the Parliamentary Committee Room this evening.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Sharif was exempted from personal appearance at the
Supreme Court Tuesday because of the visit by U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister was directed by the apex court to
appear in person again today. The proceeding, which lasted for
more than two hours, ended with formal framing of charges against
Sharif and others.
</P>
<P>
In the event of any decision against the prime minister by the
apex court, Sharif will be deemed to be disqualified as a member
of the National Assembly, thereby losing his premiership.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that any reconciliation, if possible, between
the executive and the judiciary may avert the current crisis.
However, this depends entirely on what course of action the
government will adopt.
</P>
<P>
Hectic efforts among the troika -- the president, the prime
minister and the chief of the army staff, are under way in the
federal capital to resolve the crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
