<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Seeks Solution to Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Diego Cordovez, special
advisor for Cyprus of U.N. Secretary-General, today conveyed an
oral message to Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides that the
U.N. chief will continue efforts for a Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez, who arrived on the island Tuesday night, had a
meeting today with Clerides in the presence of U.N. officials in
Cyprus and Cypriot government officials.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the meeting, Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides described the meeting as "cordial." He said Cordovez'
objective is "to talk about the U.N. intention to resume
negotiations right after February's presidential elections."
</P>
<P>
"Kofi Annan's message refers to the secretary-general's
intention to continue his mission of good offices, with the
continuation of the present process, which began at Troutbeck,
has not been interrupted and continues after the elections,"
Kasoulides said.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-sponsored direct talks between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot sides took place this Summer in Troutbeck,
New York, and Glion, Switzerland, but failed to produce any
results.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy will to cross to the Turkish-controlled northern
part of Nicosia for meeting with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash. He will have another meeting with Clerides on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After his contacts on the island, Cordovez will fly on to
Athens and Ankara, the two supporters of Cyprus' conflicting
communities.
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to talk about the Cyprus issue with
European Union (EU) Commissioner for External Relations, Hans Van
den Broek, in Brussels, and the EU presidency envoy for Cyprus
Kester Heaslip in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took over the
northern third in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the island as a bizonal, bicommunal federation
through peace talks, but so far no tangible results have been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Transport Ministers to Meet in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- With two years to go
before the second UN Transport and Communications Decade for
Africa (UNTACDA II) Program comes to a close, African ministers
will assess the program's impact and devise an action plan for
the period 1998-2007.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here today by the United Nations
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) said the review of UNTACDA
II will take place at a three-day conference in Cairo, Egypt from
November 24 to 26, 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, the conference is organized by ECA
in collaboration with the government of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The release said, as a successor to the first decade program
implemented from 1978-1988, UNTACDA II's objective is to
establish an integrated transport and communications system which
will serve as a base for the physical integration of the
continent.
</P>
<P>
The agenda of the conference of ministers will include the
future of African transport, trade and facilitation, transport
and the environment, financing and private sector participation,
and capacity building.
</P>
<P>
African ministers will be joined by private sector
representatives and financiers, operators, planners, economists
and researchers, from around the world, the release added.
</P>
<P>
The conference of ministers, the standing decision-making
organ of the program, convenes at least every two years, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
It held its last meeting in Addis Ababa in 1995 to consider
the conclusion of the first mid-term evaluation of the program
under the auspices of the ECA, the lead agency, the release said,
adding that consideration led to the adoption of a plan of action
for 1995-1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
