<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Agrees to Investigate Controversial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today agreed to set up a board of inquiry to
look into last week's party convention, that scrapped the
primaries to elect party candidates for Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who just returned from London this morning, has
been meeting with several top Likud ministers and Knesset members
separately during the day to discuss the turmoil in the party
resulted from the cancellation of the primaries by the party's
central committee in last week's convention.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Silvan Shalom said that Netanyahu
promised him to implement all the recommendations of the
independent board of inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Most of Likud ministers called on the prime minister to find a
way to resume the election primaries, which conferred upon them
considerable advantage in the choice of party's candidates for
the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
They also asked Netanyahu to fire Avidor Lieberman, Prime
Minister Office's Director General, who was accused of playing
dirty tricks during the convention. But Netanyahu rejected the
call.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani that
he will meet with opposition Labor leader Ehud Barak next week to
discuss national reconciliation. However, Netanyahu gave no
commitment about forming a national unity government, saying he
first wants to stabilize the Likud.
</P>
<P>
Although Netanyahu agreed to establish the inquiry committee,
the crisis in Likud is far from over. "Until this committee not be
formed and its job not finished, I can not see that there is going to
be quiet days," said Shalom.
</P>
<P>
Some Likud Knesset members said that they will watch closely
the inquiry proceedings. And if the prime minister will not
follow it through, there would be another Likud rebellion against
Netanyahu's leadership.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, 20 Likud majors arrived in Netanyahu's
office in Jerusalem today to show their solidarity with him. They
attacked Netanyahu's critics, saying that the prime minister was
being treated unjustly over the primaries issue.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi also criticized those who are
mobilizing against Netanyahu, describing their efforts as "invalid
and subversive". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
