<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Prison Inspector Urges not to Lock up Youngsters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Youngsters under 18 years old
should not be put into jail as prisons were not equipped to handle
teenagers or reform them, British Chief Inspector of Prisons David
Ramsbotham said today.
</P>
<P>
Ramsbotham said in a report that the prisons were not equipped
to deal with the damaged and difficult young people because they
cann't provide the education and care that teenagers need.
</P>
<P>
"Of all parts of the prison system, this is the one that needs
the most attention," he added.
</P>
<P>
As of last July, there were 2,643 teenagers of 15-17 years old
in prison, an 11 percent increase since the start of the year.
Many of the inmates share living accommodation with adults.
</P>
<P>
He suggested to reform the prison system, which include remove
all under 18 from prison and reduce the time under 18 stay in
custody.
</P>
<P>
The chief inspector said he was not going to soften his stance
on young criminals, but if regimes do not address children's
needs, custody can do more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Prison Service General Director Richard Tilt
said today plans were being drawn to hold youngsters under 18
separately from other prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The new move was a response to the chief inspector's critical
report. But prison officials said the prison system is already
struggling to cope with the record population and a lack of
funding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
