<HEADLINE> UK Ministerial Cars Convert to Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 19 (Xinhua) - The British ministerial and
government cars are to be converted to run on gas, according to an
official announcement here today.
</P>
<P>
The Government has decided to gradually replace its car fleet
with vehicles that will be able to use both gas and petrol.
</P>
<P>
The Government Car Service's (GCS) has been testing and
encouraging the use of gas-fuelled vehicles since 1993.
</P>
<P>
The cost of conversion varies between 750 pounds (1200 US
dollars) to 3000 pounds (4800 US dollars) depending on the vehicle
and which gas is used.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Office said, the costs of conversion will be absorbed
by GCS and recouped over the next three years through reduced
vehicle management costs.
</P>
<P>
GCS cars are replaced every three years. The Agency replaces on
average 20 cars each year. These cars will now gradually be
replaced with vehicles converted to run on gas.
</P>
<P>
Maintenance costs of gas fuelled cars is believed significantly
lower than for petrol fuelled cars.
</P>
<P>
GCS provides cars and drivers to the Prime Minister and other
ministers. It also provides a mail distribution service to the
Government and the wider public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
