<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Asks Yeltsin to Dismiss Chubais </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma on
Wednesday passed a resolution requesting President Boris Yeltsin
to dismiss the First Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister
Anatoly Chubais, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also invited the president to send a inquiry to
the Prosecutor General "to obtain information relating to
observation of law by other top government officials."
</P>
<P>
The Duma supported Yeltsin in dismissing top federal executives
"who compromised themselves," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution pointed out that "the acute government crisis"
completely undermines the confidence in the government of Russians
driven to poverty.
</P>
<P>
It noted if Chubais, "who blackmails people in government
offices with the threat of financial instability, remains first
deputy prime minister and finance minister, this will demonstrate
the dependence of the president and prime minister and threaten
the prestige of the country."
</P>
<P>
In response to the Duma resolution, presidential press
secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky said that the president thinks the
Duma's resolutions "are not legally binding", the Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
According to Yastrzhembsky, president Yeltsin supported the
suggestion that the posts of deputy prime minister and minister in
the government should not be combined.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax citing Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin reported
that Yeltsin has no immediate plans to dismiss Chubais as First
Deputy Prime Minister but will most likely fire him as Finance
Minister.
</P>
<P>
It was said that earlier today, Duma Budget Committee chairman
Mikhail Zadornov was offered the post of finance minister and he
may agree to take over the post. 
</P>
