<HEADLINE> Kenya's Northeastern Province Declared Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi today declared the country's Northeastern Province a flood
disaster zone following persistent heavy rains in the region.
</P>
<P>
The president stated that Marsabit and Moyale districts in
Eastern Province had also been placed in the same category, Kenya
News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Moi was speaking to a delegation of women groups from Nairobi
who paid a courtesy call to him at the State House here today.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Kenyan government would continue to
monitor the rain situation in all parts of the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on October 24, the Kenyan government declared the
coastal region of the country a flood disaster zone.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that this time a lot of villages had been
submerged in in the coastal region after the Tana River burst its
banks.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Kenyans face starvation because most of the
affected areas could not be accessed by road and helicopters
could not land because of the floods, Minister in the Office of
the President John Koech was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains have claimed more than 20 lives since
mid-October with most deaths occurring in Central, Northeastern
and Coastal provinces.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's meteorological department forecast that the torrential
rains may extend into next year due to the El Nino phenomenon
which has affected the entire eastern African region, submerging
huge areas of Kenya, Ethiopia and Somalia. 
</P>
