today attacked the office of Ayatollah Houssein Ali Montazeri,
former designate successor of Iran's late supreme leader Ayatollah
Rowhollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
An informed source said the office of the leading religious
figure in the city of Qom, some 90 kilometers south of Tehran, was
stormed by angry theological instructors and students of the city.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA confirmed the incident in
a dispatch, saying the demonstrators were rallying to condemn
Montazeri's skeptical statement about the legitimacy of the
country's supreme leadership, Velayat-e-Faqih (governance of
Islamic Jurisprudence).
</P>
<P>
IRNA did not give details about Montazeri's statement. But
informed sources here said Montazeri and another prominent
religious figure Ayatollah Azari Qomi stated that the supreme
leader of the country, apparently referring to Ali Khamenei, was a
supervisor to monitor the country's affairs and should not be an
administrator to directly interfere in certain naitonal issues.
</P>
<P>
The remarks aroused sharp criticism and at today's Majlis open
session, one of the Majlis members made public a letter of the
late Iranian leader Ayatollah Rowhollah Khomeini to disgrace
Montazeri as a "simple-minded person who is not suitable to be
involved in political affairs."
</P>
<P>
Religious and political organizations issued strong-worded
statements while theological instructors and students closed their
schools and staged a protest rally to denounce the statements by
Montazeri and Qomi.
</P>
<P>
It said that police was forced to intervene, using tear gas to
disperse the furious protesters in Qom.
</P>
<P>
Several policemen were injured in the scuffle, and the office
and house of the Ayatollah are under protection of the security
forces, it added.
</P>
<P>
Montazeri had been chosen by Khomeini as his heir-designate but
was later disqualified for the job by the late leader before his
death in 1989. 
</P>
