<HEADLINE> S. Leone Hunter Militias Attack Junta Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The cease fire in Sierra Leone
under a peace accord seems to be out of the window following
reports of renewed attacks by hunter militias against soldiers of
the military junta over the past days.
</P>
<P>
The hunter militias known as Kamajors loyal to President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah who was outed in the May 25 coup this year, have
intensified pressure on the military junta by fresh attacks in
the southeast region between Tongo and Kenema.
</P>
<P>
Heavy gunfire was heard in the diamond-rich town of Tongo in
the Kenema district last night, the British Broadcasting
Corporation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors have held all the roads leading to Tongo, said
residents fleeing from there to the capital Freetown today.
</P>
<P>
They have warned all the civilians to leave the town by
November 28 before they launch an all-out attack against the
junta forces who have held the town since the coup.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people have reportedly fled Tongo and reached
Kenema today.
</P>
<P>
The attacks have been described as a breach of the peace
accord signed last month in Conakry, Guinea, which calls for
cease fire in the country.
</P>
<P>
Aliu Kamara, the junta spokesman, said this afternoon that the
ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary Council will report the
incidents to the west African peace keeping force (ECOMOG).
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG is mandated by the west African countries to monitor
the peace process in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
According to the Conakry peace plan, the junta is to hand over
power to Kabbah in April next year while all people with guns,
including the junta soldiers, the Kamajors and other factions,
will be disarmed beginning from December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
