controversial labor bill, which provides for a maximum 45-hour
working week and other labor privileges, cleared the National
Council of Provinces (NCOP) today.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Conditions of Employment Bill was approved by the
National Assembly on November 6.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the NCOP Labor Committee rejected 20
last-minute amendments introduced by the National Party (NP) to
make the bill more flexible and reduce the powers of labor
Minister Tito Mboweni.
</P>
<P>
The bill was supported by black-based parties like the African
National Congress, the Inkatha Freedom Party and the Pan
Africanist Congress, but was opposed by NP, Democratic Party and
Freedom Front.
</P>
<P>
It was also rejected by organized business, which claims it
will lead to major job losses.
</P>
<P>
However, the months-old wrangling is not over as Mboweni has
told the NCOP that parliament would entertain an amendment to the
bill next year before it is promulgated.
</P>
<P>
He said much work has yet to be done. An investigation into
its possible impact on small businesses needed to be finalized
and maternity benefits provided for by the Unemployment Insurance
Fund (UIF) needed to be improved.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department had also to launch changes introduced by
the new legislation, he said. 
</P>
