<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today accused the
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK), a major party in northern
Iraq, of creating fresh tensions in the region, according to the
Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan said at a news
briefing today that it was the PUK that provoked the recent
clashes with its rival Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP).
</P>
<P>
The pro-Iranian PUK, and KDP, allegedly backed by Turkey and
Iraq, have engaged in continuous battles for the control of
northern Iraq since President Saddam Hussein was rendered
ineffective in the area by the defeat in the 1990 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Their conflicts intensified since mid-October, causing grave
concern in Turkey, the United States and Britain, the three
mediators of the Ankara process designed to settle the northern
Iraq issue.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Foreign Ministry also warned the PUK office in Ankara
against its cooperation with the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK),
Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
Ankara has repeatedly blamed the PUK for close ties with the
PKK, a outlawed militant group fighting against government troops
for autonomy in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Local TV and newspaper reports said that the KDP has assisted
Turkish troops in massive military actions against the PUK and PKK.
</P>
<P>
However, Utkan emphasized that Turkey's military operation in
northern Iraq is completely aimed at wiping out the PKK camps
there. 
