<HEADLINE> Bashir Attacks US In Response To American Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar
al-Bashir today condemned the United States' recent decision to
impose economic sanctions on Sudan, describing the U.S. as a thief
plundering and robbing Sudan's wealth.
</P>
<P>
Bashir made the remarks at a government-organized mass rally
here in protest against the U.S. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Washington announced early this month new and extensive
economic sanctions against Sudan for its alleged support for
international terrorism and human rights record. The sanctions
include freezing all Sudanese assets in the U.S. and barring
U.S. investment, bank loans and trade on selected items.
</P>
<P>
Bashir described the latest American decision, which opened the
door to the Sudanese to migrate to the U.S., as a new method of
slavery and to recruit the Sudanese people against their own
country. He said "we shall endeavor to stop this immigration,"
asserting his country will reply to the (U.S.) decision with further
holy war.
</P>
<P>
Bashir also condemned the U.S. for imposing sanctions on Iraq,
Libya and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government has adopted several measures in protest
against the U.S. sanctions. It has banned the export of Arabic Gum
to America, boycotted dealings in U.S. dollars in Sudanese banks
and prohibited the activities of U.S. firms on Sudanese
territory. Mass rallies were also organized throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the Sudanese government considered the
U.S. decision as a cause of aborting the recent negotiations in
the Kenyan capital Nairobi between the government and the major
rebel group. 
</P>
