<HEADLINE> El Nino to Hit Rice Bowls of 5 Million Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 19 (Xinhua) -- An estimated five
million people in southern Africa will need food aid over the
next nine months because of drought caused by the El Nino weather
phenomenon, World Food Program (WFP) said here today.
</P>
<P>
WFP executive director Catherine Bertini said southern African
countries had to brace themselves for possibly the worst drought
to hit the region in 100 years.
</P>
<P>
"About 27 million people live in the high risk countries of
Lesotho, Swaziland, Malawi, Madagascar, Tanzania and Zambia. Of
these about five million will be very vulnerable," she told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
She said Botswana, Namibia, South Africa and some parts of
Zimbabwe were likely to be less affected because of their
capacity.
</P>
<P>
"If we are to feed about five million people for nine months,
this would require about 600,000 tons (of food) and at about 300
U.S. Dollars per ton, we would be looking at roughly 200 million
U.S. Dollars."
</P>
<P>
Bertini is in the region to assess individual countries'
preparation for the El Nino, which is brought about by the
warming of ocean temperatures in the eastern equatorial Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
She said South Africa plays a crucial role in the relief work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
