<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Housing Starts Pick Up in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Led by apartment
construction, the U.S. housing starts rose 1.4 percent in October,
the Commerce Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth was limited to multifamily homes as a
double-digit decline in the Northeast held back single-family
construction.
</P>
<P>
The department said construction of new homes and apartments
totaled a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.53 million, the
highest since 1.55 million last February.
</P>
<P>
The October rate was up from a revised 1.51 million in the
previous month. The September rate initially was estimated to be
1.5 million in the monthly report.
</P>
<P>
Starts during the first 10 months of 1997 totaled 1.3 percent
less than they did during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Home Builders is predicting a
slight decline in sales during the fourth quarter, which would
provide fewer incentives to pour additional foundations.
</P>
<P>
Applications for building permits, often a barometer of future
activity, did slow in October, rising just 1.1 percent to a 1.48
million annual rate following September's 4.5 percent surge.
Still, the October rate was the strongest since a 1.49 million
rate in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
Single-family starts, about 80 percent of the total, fell 3.8
percent to a 1.14 million rate after jumping 8.8 percent a month
earlier.
</P>
<P>
But construction of apartments and condominiums shot up 20.6
percent to a 386,000 rate following September's 5.3 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, starts in the Northeast plunged 15.4 percent to a
115,000 rate. That offset gains elsewhere which include 3.6
percent in the West to a 378,000 rate; 3.6 percent in the Midwest
to 318,000, and 2.6 percent in the South to a 717,000. Activity in
the South was the strongest since a 728,000 rate in July 1995. At
the same time, the West registered the highest total since a
394,000 rate in April 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
