<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Meeting Convenes for Closer Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, CANADA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The annual
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum kicked off here
today with Senior officials sitting down to prepare ground for the
leaders' conference scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials representing 18 economies on the Pacific Rim
gathered in the Vancouver Trade &AMP; Convention Center this morning
for two-day meeting in preparation for the summit, the fifth since
1993.
</P>
<P>
They are discussing ways of promoting free trade and
investment, a target set in Borgor APEC summit. The developed
economies were committed to realizing the goal no later than 2010
and the developing ones no later than 2020.
</P>
<P>
Functioning as a governmental forum since its founding in 1989,
it groups Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, Hong Kong of
China, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New
Zealand, Papua New Guinea, the Philippines, Singapore, Chinese
Taipei, Thailand, the United States.
</P>
<P>
The APEC has made a remarkable progress in terms of free trade
and investment, but it remains stagnant in some other areas, an
Asian diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
The trade and investment liberalization is almost on track and
progressing, while the developed economies are showing little
interest in promoting technological cooperation, said the official
specialized in the APEC affairs.
</P>
<P>
He described the free trade and investment and economic
technological cooperation as two cornerstones of the APEC, which
makes up 40 percent of the world's total trade.
</P>
<P>
Canada, chairing this annual APEC meeting, had announced that
it would push for closer cooperation in lowering trade barriers,
strengthening infrastructure and sustaining economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The senior officials' gathering will be followed by a two-day
ministerial meeting on Friday and Saturday to finalize the agenda
for the leaders' meeting to be held next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The leaders are expected to arrive on Saturday or Sunday.
Bilateral meetings will be held on the sideline of the summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
