<HEADLINE> Cross Burned at Afro-American Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Officials are asking for
the public's help in solving a cross burning at the Afro-American
Museum and Cultural Center in Wilberforce, Ohio, of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Museum Curator Floyd Thomas found the partially burned cross
Tuesday near the museum's administrative offices.
</P>
<P>
The four-foot-high wooden cross was painted with a racial
threat, white supremacy slogans, a swastika and the Ku Klux Klan's
initials.
</P>
<P>
Ohio Highway Patrol spokesman Lt. John Born told the Columbus
Dispatch there were no suspects, saying the patrol is
investigating because the cross was burned on state property. The
Ohio Historical Society owns the museum, founded in 1988 by acts
of the Ohio General Assembly and Congress.
</P>
<P>
Thomas said the cross will probably be placed on display after
the patrol ends its investigation.
</P>
<P>
Thomas said, "It's an important part of Afro-American and
American history. This could cause people to look at the
institution and understand what we are doing here." 
</P>
</TEXT>
