<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Launches Shuttle Columbia for Science Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. space shuttle
Columbia, carrying an multinational crew of six on a 16-day
science mission, today blasted into orbit from the Kennedy Space
Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
The 4.5 million-pound spaceship was launched into a hazy sky at
2:46 p.m. EST (1946 GMT), right on the mark, as the clouds turned
out to be not as thick as forecasters had feared.
</P>
<P>
During the long-time orbit journey, Columbia's astronauts will
release a solar observatory and retrieve it two days later,
conduct a practice spacewalk that was canceled last year because
of a stuck hatch, and grow plants and crystals.
</P>
<P>
It is the eighth and final shuttle launch by the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) in the year and the
24th flight for NASA's oldest shuttle. NASA last flew eight
missions in a single year in 1992.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, NASA's astronaut Winston Scott and Japanese
astronaut Takao Doi will walk into the open cargo bay to test an
extendible crane and other equipment to be used on the future
international space station. A free-flying, ball-shaped robotic
camera will hover over the shoulders of the astronauts, making its
space debut.
</P>
<P>
Among the first astronauts to fly on a U.S. spacecraft were
also a Ukrainian and an Indian-born woman as well as Doi, who will
also be the first Japanese to make a space talk.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma attended the launch, cheering
on Columbia the Ukrainian crewman, Leonid Kadenyuk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
