<HEADLINE> Five-Nation Meeting Brings Hope for Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Intensive diplomatic efforts by
the Five U.N. Security Council permanent members seems to have
brought the Iraq weapons inspection crisis back on a peaceful
track.
</P>
<P>
News from the Geneva ministerial meeting of the five permanent
members today indicates that Baghdad has agreed to allow the
U.N. weapons inspectors, including those from the United States,
to resume their normal work in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
If Iraq announces this decision today as it has promised, no
major excuse will be left for those threatening to use force.
</P>
<P>
A carefully-worded joint statement issued at the end of the
meeting urged Iraq to unconditionally accept the return of the
U.N. inspection team in its previous composition.
</P>
<P>
The statement also suggested that the Special Commission of the
U.N. Security Council (UNSCOM) discuss ways to make its work more
effective on the basis of U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Although the statement has made no promise to Iraq, it did
offer Iraq with a ladder to climb down without losing face.
</P>
<P>
Sha Zukang, representing Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen
at the meeting, said that all the parties present share the wish
to resolve the dispute through diplomatic channels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
