<HEADLINE> South Korea Win Two more Titles in World Taekwondo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 20 (Xinhua) -- South Korea won two more
gold medals on the second day of the 13th Men's and Sixth Women's
Taekwondo World Championships here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the men's fly weight category final, South Korean Seung Tae
Chin beat Chinese Taipei's Tsai Yi-Ta to take the title.
</P>
<P>
In the women's welter weight category final, South Korea's Cho
Hyang Mi defeated Karpathaki Drosidou of Greece for South Korea's
third gold medal at the championships.
</P>
<P>
South Korea won the women's light weight category on the
championships' opening day on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the women's fly weight category final, 15-year-old middle
school student Chin Shu-Ju from Chinese Taipei downed South
Korea's Song Hee Yoon to take the first gold medal for her team at
the championships.
</P>
<P>
And the gold medal of the men's welter weight category went to
Spanish Joes Jesus Marquez who beat Germany's Marco Scheiterbauer
for the crown.
</P>
<P>
Some 600 athletes from 93 countries and regions are competing
in the five-day championships, the largest sporting event Hong
Kong has ever staged and the first world-class event held in Hong
Kong after it became China's Special Administrative Region on July
1 this year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 16 gold medals are on offer for the eight categories
each in the men's and women's divisions.
</P>
<P>
Taekwondo will be listed for the first time as an Olympic sport
 at the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000, with four categories each
for men and women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
