<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Citizens to Know More of Their Single Market Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- European Union citizens are
to learn more about their single market rights as the 15-nation
union enters later this month the second stage of its Citizen
First campaign.
</P>
<P>
Single market rights are of great interest to people in buying
goods and services in the single market, traveling in another EU
country and equal rights and opportunities for women and men.
</P>
<P>
Millions of copies of single market rights brochure will be
distributed in 19 different languages while free phone call
services and signpost services will also be provided in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
There is an Internet address dedicated to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
All these are aimed at explaining in detail how citizens can
use and enforce their rights in each EU member state and at
helping people when they have difficulties in knowing how to
exercise their rights.
</P>
<P>
There will also be a major publicity and media campaign in all
the 15 EU member states to advertise the single market rights
initiative and to inform people details of the appropriate points
of contact at European, national and local level.
</P>
<P>
Questions raised by EU citizens are deemed of importance to the
European Commission, the executive agency of the European Union,
in that they give the commissioners a direct feedback about
practical problems which people face when using their rights.
</P>
<P>
A consumer campaign will be waged in Spain, Portugal, Italy,
Greece and Ireland in the meanwhile to publicize EU legislation on
unfair contract terms and reinforcing the role of consumer bodies
in these countries.
</P>
<P>
The Single Market Action Plan endorsed at the Amsterdam summit
in June provides for the establishment of a permanent dialogue
with citizens.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue, a major feedback from a wide range of subject
areas such as employment, health protection, safety at work,
environment and food safety, will not only increase awareness of
EU rights but help sustain the awareness in the long run as well.
</P>
<P>
The provision of better access to the rights information for
business sector is another important commitment of the Single
Market Action Plan.
</P>
<P>
Planning is now underway to design a business signpost service
in the hope of guiding businesses to the correct network or body
to provide them with the information they need on single market
issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Rejects Turkish Cypriot Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
dismissed as "utterly unacceptable" terms put forward by the
Turkish Cypriot leader for participation in accession talks with
the European Union (EU), scheduled for April next year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before a Cabinet meeting today, Foreign
Minister Ioannis Kasoulides warned Rauf Denktash that "this kind
of tactics would not bear fruit."
</P>
<P>
Denktash has reportedly said that he would adopt a more
conciliatory stand if his self-styled regime in northern Cyprus is
recognized by the international community as a "sovereign entity"
and if Turkey is included among the candidates for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus", which was recognized only by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"Such statements are utterly unacceptable and this type of
policy will not get anywhere," the Cypriot foreign minister
commented.
</P>
<P>
The EU has reaffirmed its March 1995 decision that accession
negotiations with Cyprus will start early next year. Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides asked the Turkish Cypriot side to join
Greek Cypriots to form a delegation as the sole interlocutor in
the EU talks.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has turned down the proposal and warned that the
opening of talks on Cyprus' accession to EU will have adverse
effect on the pursuit of a settlement of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
"The illegal Turkish Cypriot regime will not be recognized
under any form, excuse or method. This was made abundantly clear
by the international community," Kasoulides stressed.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council described the Turkish Cypriot regime
as "legally invalid" and called in its resolution 541 (1983) for
its withdrawal, urging all states not to recognize it.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over northern third of the island in the wake of
a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
