<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Posts 6.3 Percent Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 20 (Xinhua) -- South Korea, which has been in a
financial turmoil for weeks, reported a 6.3 percent year-on-year
growth in the third quarter on back of robust exports.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Korea said in a report, "Major economic indicators
show that the national economy achieved a modest, though not
strong, growth in the third quarter, thanks mainly to a surge in
exports and a slowdown in imports."
</P>
<P>
Citing a drop in inventories and a slowdown in private
consumption, the bank said that the GDP showed a better
performance in the third quarter than in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
Merchandise exports rose 31.3 percent, while service exports
went up by 18.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the imports of goods and services expanded
by only 5.4 percent, down from 8.4 percent and 7.9 percent in the
previous two quarters.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributed the export surge to stronger price
competitiveness arising from the depreciation of the country's
currency won.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector grew 8.1 percent in the third quarter,
up from the second quarter's 7.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank predicted the economy will grow 6-6.3 percent in the
fourth quarter on an annual basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
