<HEADLINE> UN Arms Inspectors to Return to Iraq Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations arms
inspectors, including the six Americans expelled last week, would
return to Iraq and resume their work on Friday, Richard Butler,
Chairman of the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) told
CNN this morning.
</P>
<P>
Iraq Government announced early this morning that it had agreed
to allow the arms inspectors to return to Iraq immediately.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came a few hours after foreign ministers of
Britain, France, Russia and the United States and the
representative of the Minister of Foreign Affairs of China held
talks on the crisis in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Some 74 UN inspectors are awaiting in Baghrain for orders to
return to Iraq, who withdrew form Iraq last week.
</P>
<P>
The latest crisis over the weapons inspection in Iraq began on
October 29 when Iraq Government announced to expel Americans
working for the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Russia on Wednesday initiated the holding of ministerial talks
in Geneva which was aimed to find a diplomatic solution to the
crisis. 
</P>
