<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Efforts to Control Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- China plans to allocate over
180 billion yuan (21.6 billion US dollars) for pollution control
and environmental protection projects by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhehua, director of the State Bureau of Environmental
Protection, said today that efforts will focus on basically
curbing the escalation of environmental pollution and ecological
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Xie made the remarks during the ongoing "97 China
Environmental Forum," the first high-level international forum of
it's kind held in China.
</P>
<P>
He said China will focus on a series of major environmental
projects in accordance with basic state policies and the
requirements of international conventions.
</P>
<P>
The state environmental protection plan calls for China to
basically control the escalation of environmental pollution and
ecological destruction by the end of this century, in addition to
basically changing related conditions by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Xie said that massive allocations will flow into 1,600
environmental projects, including controlling water pollution
along the Huaihe, Liaohe and Haihe rivers, as well as lakes such
as Dianchi, Chaohu and Taihu. Funds have also been earmarked for
air pollution control projects, and controlling emissions from
power generation and metallurgical plants, as well as ozone layer
protection projects.
</P>
<P>
Xie stressed that related efforts will be based on the
principle that the enterprises responsible for pollution will be
required to use internal funds to solve related problems.
</P>
<P>
He said local governments will be required to collect funds for
environmental infrastructure projects. The central government will
support related projects by offering loans and introducing foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
Xie said China has also used loans from the World Bank, Asian
Development Bank and foreign governments to fund major
environmental projects.
</P>
<P>
The State Bureau of Environmental Protection announced today that
China will seek foreign cooperation for 70 major environmental
projects. A number of U.S. and Japanese companies attending the
ongoing conference have expressed interest in various projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
