</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright arrived in
Geneva to try to bring an end to the crisis with Iraq. Ms.
Albright and the Foreign Ministers of Russia, Britain and France
agreed to meet to see if Iraq was willing to retreat from its
challenge to the United Nations under terms the United States will
accept.
</P>
<P>
-- The space shuttle Columbia flew into orbit, executing a
180-degree roll at the start of its mission. The flip put the
shuttle in radio contact with communication satellites, which was
necessary because a tracking station in Bermuda will soon be shut
down to save money.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov told
representatives of the United Nations Security Council early today
that Iraq is prepared to back down from its confrontation with the
United Nations over weapons inspections, and an announcement to
that effect is expected later today, Secretary of State madeleine
K. Albright announced.
</P>
<P>
-- An Iowa woman gave birth yesterday to what may be the
world's first surviving set of septuplets, making medical history
with the successful delivery of four boys and three girls.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Pacific Rim trading partners meet this weekend in Canada,
and U.S. President Bill Clinton, in contrast with the session
held just after his Nafta victory four years ago, will arrive
still smarting from the House's blow to his "fast-track" trade
legislation. He plans to underscore that the U.S. is committed
to liberalized trade.
</P>
<P>
-- Yeltsin removed deputy premiers Anatoly Chubais and Boris
Nemtsov from second positions as finance minister and energy
minister, respectively. The move averted a showdown with Russian
lawmakers who threatened to derail next year's budget, in the wake
of a book-advance scandal implicating Chubais. 
</P>
