<HEADLINE> South Korean Currency Plunges 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 20 (Xinhua) -- South Korean currency fell 10
percent to the daily allowable low for the first time today after
the government announced a package of measures to stablize the
troubled financial market.
</P>
<P>
Today's trading totaled about 100 million U.S. dollars, dealers
said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the sharp depreciation of won, the central bank didn't
intervene in the domestic foreign-exchange market. It supplied
dollars only to those who could prove to be in real need.
</P>
<P>
The won, which hit its daily lows for the fourth consecutive
day, has depreciated about 35 percent sine the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed won's fall to strong speculative
forces and high demand for dollars among exporters.
</P>
<P>
Market experts predicted that the foreign exchange instability
would go on for a couple of days more.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, share prices at the Seoul stock exchange dropped
14.18 points to close at 488.41 despite the government's
stabilization measures, dealers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
