<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bayer Remains Committed to Asia after Currency Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Chemicals and
pharmaceuticals group Bayer remains committed to its expansion
plans in Asia despite the recent currency turmoil in the region.
</P>
<P>
Bayer management board spokesman for Asia Pacific Dieter Becher
 announced here today that the multinational company will spend
2.32 billion U.S. dollars over the next ten years on capital
expenditures and acquisitions in the region, with the aim of
increasing Asia's share in total group sales from 14 percent in
1996 to 25 percent by 2010.
</P>
<P>
"Bayer has no intention to slow down the implementation of its
marketing and investment plans for Asia," he told a media
briefing, expressing strong confidence in the region.
</P>
<P>
Macroeconomic realignments after the currency crisis "will
rather help to strengthen the economic development of the emerging
 economies in Asia," Becher pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The currency woes did not come as a complete surprise to Bayer
and "have only marginally impacted the sales and profit
performance so far", he added.
</P>
<P>
During the first nine months of 1997, Bayer recorded a sales
increase of 11 percent in Asia-Pacific to 3.25 billion
U.S. dollars, in line with the 13 percent rise across the globe to
 23.95 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turning to China, Becher revealed that Bayer enjoyed a path of
steady growth in the country, with a 12 percent increase in sales
in the first nine months of 1997 and an annual growth of 13
percent over the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
Currently, ten joint ventures have been put into operation in
China while another five are being discussed.
</P>
<P>
A state-of-the-art healthcare plant located in Beijing will
start production in the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
So far Bayer has invested 290 million U.S. dollars in China and
 it envisages to inject another 290 million U.S. dollars into the
country by 2010, said Becher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
