<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress Made on East Timor, Says Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 20 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said today after talks with visiting Indonesian
President Soeharto that progress has been made on the East Timor
problem, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that we are making progress, whenever we sit
down and discuss, we open the way for further progress," Mandela
told reporters in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
"Our discussions today have been very fruitful."
</P>
<P>
But he did not say whether he had again appealed to Soeharto
for the release of jailed East Timorese leader Xanana Gusmao.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo told reporters last
week that Mandela would renew his appeal to Soeharto for Gusmao's
release.
</P>
<P>
Mandela made his first appeal in a letter to Soeharto after
his return from a state visit to Indonesia in July.
</P>
<P>
Mandela refused to go to detail on this issue, saying that he
would first report to UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan, with whom
he had been in contact three times in recent days.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, with a silent Soeharto at his side, appealed to the
media to respect his constitutional right to keep confidential
what he has discussed with the Indonesian leader.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he was not acting independently, but was part of
the UN efforts to find a lasting solution to the dispute.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former colony of Portugal, was occupied by
Indonesia in 1975 and annexed in the following year as
Indonesia's 27th province.
</P>
<P>
But the UN does not recognize Jakarta's sovereignty over the
territory and still regards Portugal as its legitimate
administrator.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are trying to negotiate an internationally
acceptable solution to the question.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto arrived in South Africa from Namibia this morning for
a three-day state visit.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the two countries are expected to sign two
accords to boost trade relations.
</P>
<P>
An aviation agreement will facilitate direct air links between
the tow countries, while a trade agreement will provide for a
joint economic commission.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is also reportedly interested in buying South
African armaments, especially the Rooivalk attack helicopter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
