<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Loans to Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) said today it has approved two loans totaling 150 million
U.S. dollars for the development of Bangladesh's domestic capital
market and its rural infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
An interest-free concessional loan of 80 million dollars will
be given to Bangladesh for a three-year Capital Market Development
Program, the Manila-based financial body said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The program will create a policy environment conducive to the
orderly growth of the domestic capital market and help establish
the institutional infrastructure necessary to sustain the capital
market's long-term development.
</P>
<P>
Low savings and investment rates are restricting economic
growth in Bangladesh, the ADB said, adding that the capital market
can provide alternative means for channeling domestic savings and
foreign investments into the Bangladeshi economy.
</P>
<P>
Another 70 million dollars interest-free loan from the ADB will
be granted to Bangladesh to improve poor rural infrastructure in
the north and northwest of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
