<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Envisages Financial System for Market Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- China will strive to establish
a financial system that meets the requirements of the development
of a socialist market economy in about three years, according to a
national financial conference which ended here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The system will cover financial institutions, markets and
supervision, according to the three-day conference organized by
the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and
the State Council, which ended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
China must significantly raise the operational and management
levels of its financial sector, improve the national financial
order, ward off financial risks, and increase its ability to
prevent and counter financial risks. These steps must be taken to
create the right conditions for further reforms, opening-up and
modernization.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the CPC Central
Committee, Premier Li Peng and Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji, both
members of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the
CPC Central Committee, made important speeches at the meeting. Hu
Jintao and Vice-Premier Li Lanqing, both also members of the
Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central
Committee, attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The three-day financial conference was the first national
meeting held by the CPC Central Committee and the State Council
after the 15th National Congress of the CPC in September.
</P>
<P>
The main agenda of the meeting is to make concrete arrangements
for resolving the major issues in financial reform and development
in accordance with Deng Xiaoping's theory and the spirit of the
15th CPC National Congress.
</P>
<P>
The meeting made a comprehensive appraisal of China's present
economic and financial situation and emphasized the importance and
urgency of further financial reforms, straightening out the
financial order and preventing and warding off financial risks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
