<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Inflation Rate Reaches 3.9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Inflation rate between January
and September this year in Macao reached 3.9 percent, latest
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics Department
show that the average composite consumer price index (CCPI) rose
3.9 percent in the first nine months.
</P>
<P>
The index between September this year and the same month last
year grew four percent when compared with the previous same
12-month period.
</P>
<P>
The price index in September rose 0.1 percent from August,
mainly due to price rise in the service sector. The price index of
transportation, garment and footwear, however, dropped 0.5
percent. The index of foodstuff dropped 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate for the whole year of 1996 was 4.8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Envisages Financial System for Market Economy (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, in this good economic situation, it is necessary to be
sober-minded about the problems existing in the financial sphere,
which include the inability of the financial system to meet the
needs to cope with economic reform and development under the new
situation, the imperfections in the legal system, weak financial
supervision, and relative confusion in the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Solving these problems is the key to the success of reforms and
the maintenance of stability both now and in the future, and a
greater effort must be made in the financial sector to ensure
financial safety, efficiency and stability, with modern
information technology and management.
</P>
<P>
To solve financial problems and promote the reforms and
development of the financial sector, banks must become real banks
in keeping with the requirements of the socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
The supervisory function of the People's Bank of China, or the
central bank, should be intensified, the pace of commercialization
of state-owned commercial banks should be accelerated, and a
multi-tier system of financial institutions should also be
established.
</P>
