<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Stocks Slide Amid Fears of Rising Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong share prices slid
further today amid concern that interest rates could be pushed up
again due to the collapse of the South Korean currency.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index, which traces the performance of 33
blue chips, declined 103.68 points, or 1.02 percent, to end the
day at 10,050.68. The market has lost for three consecutive days
about 370 points after rebounding 460 points on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Turnover shrank to 7.516 billion HK dollars (one billion US
dollars), less than half of the daily average over the past few
months.
</P>
<P>
The ten-percent plunge of the South Korean won today
intensified the concern that the Hong Kong dollar's peg to the
greenback might be tested again, said securities analysts.
</P>
<P>
The high interest rates, which have not come down yet after the
last round of speculative attack, climbed up again amid the fear.
The primary three-month interbank lending rates ticked up to 12.5
percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Herbert Lau, a researcher of Vickers Ballas Hong Kong, said:
"Interest rates will continue to be the key signal for the market
direction in the next few weeks." He predicted that the market
would be volatile before the end of the year, with the blue-chip
index moving up and down around the 10,000-point level.
</P>
<P>
Shares opened slightly lower today, and dropped to 9980.25
points before the midday close, but finally recovered to cling to
the 10,000-point benchmark.
</P>
<P>
Utilities shares led the decline, shedding 241.85 points or
2.18 percent, followed by property, commerce and industry
counters, H shares and red chips, which all fell modestly. Bank
shares bucked the trend to move up by some 12 points.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
