<HEADLINE> Beijing Puts Checks on Judicial Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING. November 20 (Xinhua) -- A local regulation passed here
today gives the Beijing People's Congress the right to limit
judicial departments in their handling of legal cases.
</P>
<P>
From next year on, the standing committee of the Beijing
People's Congress will have special committees to look into
appeals, accusations and reports made by citizens or organizations
against judicial organizations and their staff members.
</P>
<P>
"The new regulation is a major step by the municipal government
to perfect the supervisory system and ensure that judicial
departments do their duties in accordance with the law," said Xu
Bingzhong, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the Beijing
People's Congress, the city's legislature.
</P>
<P>
"It will put a check on judicial departments and stop abuses of
power, fraudulent practices, and embezzlement," said Liu Changyi,
a legislator.
</P>
<P>
The ruling will take effect January 1 for Beijing's courts,
procuratorates, public security offices, and prisons.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, the standing committee can form a
special investigative committee, ask judicial departments to
report to it on specific cases, examine files, suggest that
judicial departments correct wrongdoings, or reexamine specific
cases.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also has articles to ensure that judicial
departments remain independent of each other, and the Standing
Committee can look into cases that might be wrongly handled, Liu
explained.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 28 provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities
have similar laws or regulations on judicial supervision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
