<HEADLINE> Japan's October Trade Surplus Jumps By 139.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Japan's global merchandise trade
surplus in October more than doubled from a year earlier due to
robust exports of automobiles and office equipment and the recent
depreciation of the Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar, the
Finance Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
Japan's trade surplus for October totaled 1,107.8 billion yen
(about 8.8 billion dollars), registering a 139.7 percent
year-on-year increase, the ministry said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Of Japan's global trade in October, exports increased by 17.3
percent from a year earlier to 4,648.8 billion yen (about 36.8
billion dollars) while imports edged up by 1.2 percent to 3,541.0
billion yen (about 28.0 billion dollars), the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the United
States increased by 55.6 percent from a year earlier to 547.2
billion yen (about 4.3 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
In trade with the U.S., exports climbed by 17.7 percent to
1306.8 billion yen (about 10.3 billion dollars), while imports
edged up by 0.1 percent to 759.6 billion yen (about 6.0 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Japan also registered a continued increase in its trade surplus
with the European Union (EU) and other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The surplus with the EU grew by 25.8 percent to 752.8 billion
yen (about six billion dollars), while that with other Asian
countries surged by 51.9 percent to 549.9 billion yen (about 4.3
billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
