<HEADLINE> China's Largest Saltwater Lake Shrinking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Qinghai Lake in northwest
China's Qinghai province is losing 11 cm a year in water level
because of dry weather and biological degradation, according to an
international conference.
</P>
<P>
Drought and serious soil erosion have caused a major decrease
in the flow of the Yellow River, a major source of the lake's
water, causing the lake's water level to drop, according to Liu
Guanghe, vice-governor of Qinghai Province, who is attending the
1997 China Environmental Forum in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The lake, which lies 3,200 meters above sea level in Qinghai
province, is China's largest lake and largest saltwater lake, and
is fed by seven rivers.
</P>
<P>
The lake has an average depth of 19 meters and is over 30
meters at the deepest.
</P>
<P>
Liu explained that Qinghai's forest coverage is only 2.59
percent and 330,000 sq km of land, or 46 percent of the province's
total, suffer from soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
The province has worked out a 15 to 20-year plan to control
soil erosion by planting trees and growing grass and by developing
environmentally friendly agriculture and animal husbandry, as well
as environmental protection in the areas along the lake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Allows Return of US Arms Inspectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Iraq announced today that it
will allow the U.N. arms inspection teams, including U.S. arms
inspectors, to return to Iraq and resume their work starting today
in accordance with an agreement reached with Russia.
</P>
<P>
This came in a joint statement issued simultaneously in
Baghdad and Moscow today following a visit by Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz to Moscow, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached following exchange of letters
between Iraqi President Saddam Hussein and his Russian
counterpart Boris Yeltsin, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
"Russia will actively contribute -- provided that Iraq will
implement the relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions -- to
getting the sanctions imposed on Iraq lifted soon, and will seek
to enhance the effectiveness of the UNSCOM (U.N. Special
Commision) taking in view Iraq's sovereignty and security," said
the joint statement.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides agreed to continue making contacts with each
other in connection with the agreement they reached," the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
Aziz met with Yeltsin in Moscow Tuesday and conveyed to him a
message from Saddam Hussein in reply to a previous message sent by
the Russian president.
</P>
<P>
The messages dealt with ways of getting Iraq's current
showdown with the U.N. settled diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
INA also said that a joint meeting of Iraq's Revolutionary
Command Council and the National Command of the ruling Baath
party was in session to discuss the Baghdad-Moscow joint
statement and that a statement would be issued following the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The agency reported that Saadoun Hammadi, Speaker of the
Iraq's National Assembly (Parliament), briefed members of the
assembly this morning on the positive results achieved through
messages exchanged between the Iraqi and Russian leaders as well
as the results achieved by Aziz in lifting the seven-year-old
U.N. embargo imposed on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq following its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions cannot be lifted unless the U.N. arms inspection
teams verify that Iraq has eliminated all its weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The current U.N.-Iraqi confrontation was caused by Iraqi
expulsion of U.S. arms inspectors in the UNSCOM teams on November
13. Iraq accused the Americans of conducting espionage and
blocking the lifting of the sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
