<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar lost
more than half a US cent today in a bearish market as a plunging
South Korean won took the center stage.
</P>
<P>
The local unit settled at 68.61 US cents, down from a close
yesterday of 69.35 US cents.
</P>
<P>
Traders said concerns over the financial crisis in Asia and its
likely negative implications for the domestic economy continued.
</P>
<P>
"Every factor that is coming out at the moment is still
negative" for the Australian dollar, Paul Macarounas, a foreign
exchange expert, said.
</P>
<P>
"The Asia problem is not getting any better. The Aussie is
losing its shine as an interest rate currency and certainly as a
commodity based currency," the expert said.
</P>
<P>
Today, the focus was on the South Korean currency market where
trade was again suspended as the won plunged past the lower limit
of the 10 per cent band set around 1012.8 won, falling to an
all-time low of 1,035.5 won against the United States dollar.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is Australia's second largest export destination
and has a strong appetite for commodities, particularly copper and
aluminum.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was weaker against the yen as traders
said Japanese investors looked to cover shorts.
</P>
<P>
The local unit was at 86.89 yen, from yesterday's close of
87.98 yen and at 1.1899 marks from 1.2063 marks previously.
</P>
</TEXT>
