<HEADLINE> Share Prices Decline Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined
sharply on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index lost 39.94 points to close at 1641.03 points
today.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the local market was dragged down by the
market chaos in neighboring Malaysia. "If Malaysia keeps going
down, then the Singapore shares must also be hurt," one dealer at
a local brokerage firm said.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume increased to 250.16 million units, valued
at 490.71 million Singapore dollars (306.69 million US dollars).
Declines overwhelmed advances by 339 to 39, while 234 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Magnum Corporation was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 15.96 million units. It was followed by
Progen which had 14.04 million shares traded. RHB Capital was next
with 10.1 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 60 cents to finish at 13.8 Singapore
dollars. Creative 50 gained 50 cents to end at 45.6 Singapore
dollars, while Jurong Shipyard increased by 35 cents to close at
8.15 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, NBT was the biggest loser as it declined by
1.8 dollars to end at 20.5 Singapore dollars. Bukit Sembawang lost
90 cents to close at 12.8 Singapore dollars, and Oriental Holdings
fell by 70 cents to finish at 2.3 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
