<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's First Robot to Help in Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The first robotic
surgical assistant in Africa was introduced at a Johannesburg
hospital Wednesday, The Citizen newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Five operations were conducted with the help of the robot
named AESOP (automated endoscopic system operating procedure) at
the Park Lane Clinic in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
It was used to visually inspect the abdomen or chest via a
camera attached to a monitor.
</P>
<P>
The robot, mounted on the theater bed, can be activated
manually and via voice recognition.
</P>
<P>
It understands 23 commands, and responds by moving the camera
(endoscope) to the precise position required by the doctor to
ensure that he maintains a precise visual control of the
procedure.
</P>
<P>
It is calibrated by the surgeon with the specific data
concerning the weight and size of the patient.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Johan van der Wat, a gynecologist and endoscopic surgeon
at the clinic who pioneered the project, said robotic surgery is
the only way for surgery to go in future.
</P>
<P>
He explained that during open case surgery in the past, the
surgeon had to run the camera with his right hand, while
operating with the left hand. Now the surgeon had both hands free
and full control of his eyes.
</P>
<P>
The human assistant who had to hold the camera often had
difficulties in holding it still for a long time during complex
procedures. There were also communication problems between the
doctor and the assistant.
</P>
<P>
Jay Smith, international director of computer motion in the
United States, who is working with gynecologists and
obstetricians at the clinic said with the help of the robot, the
operating time could be reduced by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
"It is used for cardiac surgery such as an artery by-pass, in
gynecologic and general surgery," Smith said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
