<HEADLINE> Cameroun Boosting Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Cameroun's Minister of State
for Agriculture Augustin Kodock has said there is need to carry
out agricultural campaigns since Camerounians have now begun to
realize that agriculture pays, Cameroon Tribune reported today.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the declaration during a conference in the
economic capital Douala recently with fertilizer and pesticide
dealers aimed at examining farmers' problems and seeking ways and
means to improve productivity.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, the minister of state said it was due
to inadequate guarantees and the underlined means of
reimbursement of loans that banks were dragging their feet to
grant loans to dealers in fertilizers and pesticides.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that a subvention of CFA 400 million (about 6,800
U.S. Dollars) in form of fertilizers and pesticides was
distributed to the different delegations of agriculture last
year.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his ministry does not impose any particular
type of fertilizer on farmers who, he explained, choose their
fertilizers based on the results or easy application.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he added, neither fertilizers nor pesticides are
imposed on farmers. They choose from a variety of products the
national committee recommends based on their safety to man and
the environment.
</P>
<P>
On the local production of fertilizers, the minister said:
"that is even my greatest desire." He said the farmer is being
educated on the type of fertilizers to apply on what type of soil,
through district representatives of the ministry who serve as
liaison officers between the ministry and even researchers.
</P>
<P>
The minister said there is no urgency in the importation of
pesticides since files have to be studied meticulously or
prudence cannot be compromised with urgency, especially as the
slightest error results in calamity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
