<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Giant Bakun Hydro-Electric Project Taken </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government
has taken over the deferred Bakun hydro-electric project in
Sarawak, East Malaysia, from the private firm Ekran Bhd effective
today, Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim announced today.
</P>
<P>
Ekran, a major shareholder of Bakun Hydro-Electric Corporation
(BHC), is no longer keen to continue with the project, Anwar who
is also Finance Minister said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
The 13.6 billion ringgit (about 4 billion U.S. dollar) project
in Sarawak's hinterland was awarded to Ekran Bhd, which owns 32
percent of BHC, and was subsequently contracted out to a
consortium ABB-CBPO, comprising Swedish-based Asea Brown Boveri
and a Brazilian group, Companhia Brasileira de Projectos Obras.
</P>
<P>
However, Ekran dropped ABB-CBPO as the main contractor
following contractual disputes a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
The government announced in its 1998 budget that it will defer
the project along with several other big projects in the wake of
the sharp depreciation of the local currency and sharp fall in the
share prices on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange as a result of the
financial turmoil in the region.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that since Ekran had lost interest in the Bakun dam
project due to the government's firm stand to defer it, the
government had no option but to take over some of the components
of the project.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said in view of recent developments, the government would
reschedule the implementation of the project taking into account
the country's future power needs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
