<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Thai Government Presents Policy Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The new Thai government led by
Democrat Party leader Chuan Leekpai presented its policy statement
to the Parliament today, giving priority to tackling the country's
economic woes, particularly the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The restoration of confidence of both domestic and
international investors is the most urgent task of Thailand, the
government said in the 44-page statement, which covers the areas
of politics, administration, national security, foreign affairs,
social and economic development.
</P>
<P>
The government will step up its effort to stabilize the economy
and solve the problems facing the financial institutions in the
country, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The government will support and develop the financial
institutions which currently remain in operation, while moving to
bail out the cash-trapped 58 finance firms whose operations were
suspended earlier this year, including allowing them to resume
operation after capital increase.
</P>
<P>
The government also reaffirmed its commitment with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), including maintaining its
foreign exchange reserves at a level enough to build up confidence
of investors in the Thai economy.
</P>
<P>
On other economic aspects, the statement said that the
government will take measures to draw more foreign investment and
clear barriers for exports and tourism to increase the country's
revenues in foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Also, the government will take measures to help local
enterprises, especially those export-oriented enterprises which
are short of funds, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government will encourage the private sector
to take over the state-owned enterprises to lessen the state
burden and improve management.
</P>
<P>
On medium- and long-term economic policies, the statement said
that the government will strive to readjust the country's
agricultural and industrial structures, bring in new technology
and foreign funds, develop human resources to lay a solid
foundation for the country's future economic development.
</P>
<P>
On political issues, the government stressed that it will speed
up the implementation of the new Constitution and other by-laws to
push ahead the political reform in the country.
</P>
<P>
On the foreign affairs, the statement said that the Thai
government will stick to the United Nations Charter and those
treaties that Thailand has participated in and enhance its
cooperation with all countries over the world, especially its
neighboring countries in the areas of economy, science and
technology, culture, tourism and human resources development.
</P>
<P>
The statement particularly stressed that Thailand will
strengthen and improve its cooperative ties with other members of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and boost
economic ties with major trade partners under the free-trade
principle.
</P>
<P>
Among the social issues, the statement said that the government
will increase job opportunities to ease the deteriorating
employment situation caused by the economic slowdown in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the national security, the government pledges to
support the modernization of the country's armed forces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
