<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's External Trade Up 11.4 Percent in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's total trade
increased by 11.4 percent in October on a three-month moving
average basis, with exports and imports expanding by 9.4 percent
and 13.4 percent respectively, the Singapore Trade Development
Board (TDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
On a monthly basis, the TDB said, non-oil domestic exports rose
by 9.5 percent, marking the fifth consecutive month of positive
growth.
</P>
<P>
The TDB said that the increased was reflected in strong
double-digit growth of key electronic products such as integrated
circuits and Printed Circuit Board Assembled (PCBA). Besides,
domestic exports of non-electronics such as petrochemicals and
magnetic disk media also contributed to the growth.
</P>
<P>
Re-exports expanded by 8.2 percent, with the increase coming
mainly from key electronic products such as integrated circuits
and PCBA, in particular, to Malaysia, Japan and the European Union
(EU).
</P>
<P>
On a three-month moving average basis, non-oil domestic exports
increased by 10.3 percent to reach 8.4 billion Singapore dollars
(5.25 billion US dollars) in October. Of the total, non-oil
domestic exports to the United States, the EU, and Hong Kong
achieved double-digit growth of 12.3 percent, 10.2 percent and
23.9 percent respectively, the TDB said.
</P>
<P>
However, oil domestic exports continued to decline by 5.2
percent due mainly to slower demand of oil from Hong Kong and
Japan, it said.
</P>
<P>
Imports increased by 13.4 percent, amounting to 17.6 billion
Singapore dollars (about 11 billion US dollars) in October.
Increases were reflected in imports of integrated circuits,
computer parts and peripherals, disk drives, semiconductors and
parts, and other electronic products, the TDB said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
