<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The 15 members of the European Union (EU) today began its
first summit in Luxembourg which is consecrated to jobs, at a time
when 10.6 percent of the active population of EU countries are
unemployed. The EU members are expected to adopt a concerted policy
on fighting unemployment and lay out some social direction lines on
jobs to be presented by the European Commission. They will also
discuss ways to relieve enterprises from high costs in employment
and ``adapt'' the salary-owners to a more flexible labor market.
</P>
<P>
-- The communal and regional elections of Denmark held on Tuesday
confirmed the Social-Democratic Party as the leading party of the
country with 33.1 pecent of the votes, while witnessing a rise of
the extreme-right Party of the Danish People, which obtained 6.8
percent of the votes two years after its creation. The party joined
elections in 145 communes out of 275.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Urban violences come one after another everyday in France.
Over the past several days, riots took place in several French
cities, including Lille, where the arrest of a thief triggered a
riot during which public equipments and cars were burnt. The general
rise of violence came with the increasing criminal cases committed
by minors, as courts in the Paris region has multiplied by four the
number of condemnations of minors to prison.
</P>
<P>
-- Jean-Claude Juncker, the prime minister of Luxembourg and
president in exercise of the European Union (EU), told le Figaro
that the EU summit on jobs, the first of its kind, to be held today
in Luxembourg will take ``a concrete action.'' Pierre Moscovici, the
French Minister for European Affairs, said that a ``multilateral
surveillance'' system on jobs will be established by the EU during
the summit. Meanwhile, the leader of France's Confederation Generale
du Travail Louis Viannet denounced the consequences from the
implementation of the euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
