<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Large Ice Mortar Groups Discovered in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have found
two groups of ice mortars from the Quaternary Period on a stony
ridge near Chifeng City in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The two groups, which are 400 meters apart, contain more than
30 ice mortars at an elevation of 700 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
The largest is 4.5 meters in diameter and has a depth of 1.9
meters. The mouth of the ice mortar is small, the middle part is
large and the bottom part is quite flat.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Academy of Sciences and the Academy of
Geological Science say they believe the two groups are the biggest
in China and are quite unusual in the world.
</P>
<P>
Ice mortars have been found previously on Huangshan Mountain in
Anhui Province, Lushan Mountain in Jiangxi Province, and on a
mountain in Fengning County in Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the ice mortar is evidence of glacial activity
and indicates that China had large scale glacier developments
between one million and 2 million years ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran-Libya Sanctions Act Applied only in US: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 20 (Xinhua) -- United States Deputy
Assistant Secretary of State for Energy Sanctions and Commodities
William Ramsay said here today that the Iran-Libya Sanctions Act
was unilateral and applied only in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Replying to reporters after meeting with Malaysian Foreign
Ministry's Acting Undersecretary for America Division Mohd Arshad
M. Hussain, Ramsay said, "The sanctions apply domestically in the
U.S. and they are not to apply outside."
</P>
<P>
"Well, sanctions could be imposed against Iran if the United
Nations agrees to such sanctions, but I don't know of any," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The intended move by the U.S. to probe Malaysia's national oil
company Petronas' involvement in gas field development in Iran has
met with all-round condemnation in Malaysia with Parliament
passing a motion Thursday to censure the U.S. for attempting to
implement the controversial act in other countries.
</P>
<P>
Petronas, together with France's company Total SA and Russia's
Gazprom, is involved in a 2 billion U.S. dollars gas field
development in Iran, which the U.S. government says faces the risk
of sanctions under the Act passed last year, which provides for
sanctions to be applied against companies which invest more than
20 million dollars a year in the oil and gas sector in both Iran
and Libya.
</P>
<P>
Ramsay made an announcement that his visit here is not to
investigate the gas field venture between Petronas and Iran as
expected, defusing a diplomatic row between Kuala Lumpur and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
He said, "I was taking this opportunity to explain the Act and
its implementation so that the people understand. I am not here on
an investigatory mission."
</P>
<P>
He said in view of the situation, he would not be visiting
Petronas because he was satisfied with the outcome of his meeting
today with Mohd Arshad.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Malaysian Foreign Ministry said in a statement
that during Ramsay's meeting with Malaysian officials led by Mohd
Arshad, it was clarified that the Act also provides the U.S.
president with discretion to waive or delay the imposition of
sanctions under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
It said that during the meeting, Mohd Arshad reiterated
Malaysia's position that the Act did not apply to Malaysia as it
was a U.S. national legislation.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia does not accept this extra-territorial application
and Malaysia holds the view that Petronas, in participating in the
consortium to develop the South Pars Gas Field in Iran, has not
contravened Malaysian laws or any international law or any World
Trade Organization regulations," the statement quoted Mohd Arshad
as saying.
</P>
<P>
It said Mohd Arshad told the meeting that Petronas and other
Malaysian companies would continue to invest abroad wherever
economic opportunities existed, including in Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
"Notwithstanding the differences between the two countries on
the interpretations regarding the applicability of the stated U.S.
legislation, both sides agreed that the foundations of
Malaysia-U.S. relations remain strong. The two countries share a
long-standing, beneficial and important relationship based on
mutual respect and understanding," the statement said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
