<HEADLINE> Stocks Rebound in Tokyo on Hope For Public Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo stock prices rebounded
sharply today on renewed optimism over public funds following a
news report that Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
instructed the ruling Liberal Democratic Party to consider using
public funds to help troubled banks.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 466.03 points, or 2.94 percent,
from Wednesday's close to 16,308.49.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index, covering all issues
on the First Section, increased 16.42 points, or 1.34 percent to
1,238.02.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section rose to an estimated 830 million
shares, up from Wednesday's 600.17 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Failed Hokkaido Takushoku Bank was today' most actively traded
issues.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo market, which has seen steep ups and downs in recent
sessions on prospects over public funds, reacted quickly again to
the news that Hashimoto has accepted former Prime Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa's proposal for the government to use public money for
troubled banks as efforts to stabilize the country's banking
system.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar slipped to 126
Japanese yen level following the news report on the prime
minister's instruction.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 126.52-55 yen at 5 p.m., down
from 126.96-127.00 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo and from 127.00-10 yen
late Wednesday in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
