<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Announces Strategy to Reduce Greenhouse Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard today unveiled a 126 million U.S. dollar strategy that
would help reduce Australia's greenhouse gas emission growth.
</P>
<P>
Howard told the Australian parliament that the strategy, which
aims to improve the country's environment credentials ahead of
next month's climate change summit in Kyoto, Japan, would have a
dramatic impact on Australia's emission levels by 2010 compared
with the 1990 benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
Under the strategy, Australia's greenhouse gas emissions are
expected to rise by 18 percent over the 1990 levels instead of a
previously-projected 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
But Howard stressed that Australia would not agree to an
outcome at the Kyoto conference aimed at setting legally-binding
reduction targets for developed countries beyond the year 2000,
"that burdens us in an unfair manner."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Howard said that he would not sign on any
documents at the meeting if the outcome is unacceptable to
Australia's national interests.
</P>
<P>
The 18-percent increase ceiling has made Australia isolated
from other major developed countries on the greenhouse gas issue,
which have proposed reduction or stabilization targets for
greenhouse gas emissions by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) has made a proposal for greenhouse gas
emissions to be cut by 15 percent from the 1990 levels by 2010 for
developed countries, and Japan promised a 5 percent reduction in
its greenhouse gas emissions. The United States has called for
stabilization of global greenhouse gas emissions by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Environment Minister Robert Hill said that to go below the
18-percent limit would cost Australian jobs and damage sectors
where Australia has a competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
The strategy announced by Howard includes a range of programs
to encourage more efficient energy use, conversion to renewable
energy and revegetation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
