<HEADLINE> Israel Presents Final-Status Maps to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 20 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli official
has presented the United States with maps outlining Israel's
security and settlement concerns in a final-status arrangement
with the Palestinians, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, who is currently
visiting the U.S., presented the maps to U.S. national security
advisor Sandy Berger during a meeting in the White House
Wednesday, in which "Israel wants to retain several security zones
in the territories in any final-status settlement," the Radio
quoted an Israeli official as saying.
</P>
<P>
No statements were made after the meeting, but the Israeli
official said that Sharon stressed that "among the zones to be
retained by Israel are the Jordan Rift Valley, east-west roads
bisecting the territories and water resources."
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the official added, primarily dealt with the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, but not with how to make the
jump into final-status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Berger did not response immediately to the maps, but told
Sharon that the U.S. is working on its own plans for final-status
arrangements, which will be presented to Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) soon, the official said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton was reportedly not happy with the
Israeli government's hardline policy toward the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks and he refused to meet Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in the United states, even
though both of them were in Los Angeles the same day earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian Steering Committee met in Jericho, West
Bank Monday, and both sides did not reach agreements on
security-linked issues on projected Gaza airport and seaport, safe
passage between the West Bank and Gaza Strip and the Karni
Industrial Zone located near Gaza. 
</P>
</TEXT>
