<HEADLINE> France Hails Iraqi Decision to Let UNSCOM Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- France today hailed the decision
announced by the Iraqi government to unconditionally let all the
arms inspectors of the U.N. special commission on disarmament in
Iraq (UNSCOM) to return from today.
</P>
<P>
"This decision of Iraq answers the wish expressed this night
(Wednesday night) in Geneva by the five permanent members of
Security Council, who hoped a decision without condition of Iraq to
accept the return on its territory of the personnel of the United
Nations special commission in its former composition," French
Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutrizux said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Russia reached an agreement early this morning in
which Baghdad allows all arms inspectors of UNSCOM to return
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi decision came four hours after a meeting by the five
permanent members of U.N. Security Council in Geneva, who studied
the proposal presented by Russia on going out of the crisis, which
began on October 29, when Iraq announced the expulsion of U.S.
weapons inspectors from the UNSCOM team. 
