<HEADLINE> Turkey Equips its Choppers with Anti-missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Turkish military has started
to equip its helicopters with anti-missile systems purchased from
abroad, local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
These precautions were taken against possible ground attacks
from the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in southeastern
Turkey and northern Iraq, the paper quoted a senior official from
the Turkish General Staff as saying.
</P>
<P>
The source, who declined to be named, said that Greece, a
traditional rival of Turkey, had reportedly provided the PKK
rebels with anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
Two Turkish choppers involved in military operation were shot
down this summer by PKK's surface-to-air missiles. Thirteen
servicemen were killed.
</P>
<P>
These incidents led to grave concern among the military,
which urged the quick equipment of Turkey's helicopters with
anti-missiles systems.
</P>
<P>
"Reports that the PKK has purchased Stinger missiles made it
necessary to provide advanced anti-missile systems to our
military helicopters," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military has been in contact with the United States
and Israel for important deals in this field, defense sources
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
