<HEADLINE> Israel Wins Military Contract in Switzerland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Tadiran Electronic
Systems Company has won a military contract to supply command,
control, communication and intelligence systems to the Swiss army,
local daily The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Tadiran executives were quoted by the daily as saying that the
contract worth of 120 million U.S. dollars is a milestone in the
European market, as it represents a significant entry into
Switzerland and may arouse interest among other European countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli industry sources, the deal is the largest
ever won by an Israeli private defense contractor.
</P>
<P>
The Tadiran system, called C31, is meant to provide the Swiss
artillery division with real-time battlefield information on the
deployment of friendly and enemy forces.
</P>
<P>
The system comprises several portable computers and military
work stations that incorporate information technology to channel
data via radio or wire, which will improve accuracy and save
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
Tadiran Chief Executive Officer Yisrael Zamir said he is
expecting other contracts from Switzerland because the C31 system,
which he claimed to be the most advanced in the world, can be used
for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
The company won the contract through competition with British,
French and German defense firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
