<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mining Towns in China Look for Ways To Keep Developing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Workers at the Daqing Oilfield
in northeast China are using new recovery technology that will
allow them to get petroleum until the year 2010, but China will
eventually have to face the reality of shrinking oil resources.
</P>
<P>
Officials at Daqing are not quite so pessimistic about the
city's future prospects, however, and say that Daqing is fully
capable of maintaining economic prosperity for a longer period of
time by relying on new substitute industries.
</P>
<P>
They explain that Daqing has formed six major industries, and
the electronic sector alone is expected to generate 10 billion
yuan worth of output by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Fuxin, a coal city in Liaoning Province has analogous
problems. It now faces serious urban economic development problems
as a result of the rapid reduction of coal resources, and 70,000
miners face the prospect of joblessness because of a lack of coal.
</P>
<P>
City leaders in Fuxin have said they will work harder to find
new substitute industries in the next 15 years to save the city
from extinction.
</P>
<P>
China is rich in natural resources and 100 cities that depend
on the mining industry have emerged, but there are problems. They
have a single industrial structure, lack of infrastructure, a
deteriorating environment, and growing employment pressures.
</P>
<P>
Economists say that a diverse industrial structure and
developing comprehensive urban functions will be an effective way
of dealing with these problems.
</P>
<P>
Many of these mining towns are aware of their problems and have
started to invest heavily in developing mineral resources and
other sideline businesses.
</P>
<P>
A Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources official says that
adjusting the industrial structure of mining towns and developing
a diverse economy would be a second revolution, so opening wider
to the outside world and actively attracting more overseas funds
is urgent and is a natural choice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Appeals for Tariff Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) should provide for market
information systems within the national borders in order to
improve marketing and food security in the region by reducing
tariff barriers.
</P>
<P>
Addressing delegates at the agricultural food marketing
agencies of eastern and southern Africa workshop in Harare
Wednesday, Zimbabwe's grain marketing board managing director
Martin Muchero said there was need for governments to liberalize
the market by reducing tariff barriers.
</P>
<P>
He said the complete liberalization of agricultural markets
and sub-regional trade should encourage production on the basis
of comparative advantage and greater integration of the economies
of the region.
</P>
<P>
This would result in producers growing crops in response to
the demands of the market and agro-ecological conditions in their
areas, and not to government pricing policies.
</P>
<P>
There was need to have government policies harmonized and be
consistent with the promotion of free trade and the ultimate goal
should be the removal of all controls, tariffs and non-tariff
barriers on foodstuffs, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the workshop would provide a forum for food marketing
agencies to share information on agricultural production and
marketing issues in their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
Representative of the food and agriculture organization Andrew
Shepherd said that if a market was to function successfully
countries should not consider themselves to be islands.
</P>
<P>
He said attempts by governments to control imports and exports
will increase illegal trade as private traders would have more
maize available with which to exploit price differences between
countries than when most marketing was controlled by boards.
</P>
<P>
Market price mechanism should address most of the food
security concerns of governments, he said, adding the ultimate
target should be the removal of controls, tariffs and non-tariff
barriers on all foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the workshop were drawn from Kenya, Zambia,
Ethiopia, South Africa, Malawi, Mozambique and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
