<HEADLINE> Health Care Improving in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Health care standards have
greatly improved in the rural areas of northwestern China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region in the past few years because of budget
increases by the local government.
</P>
<P>
Some 160 hospitals at the township level have been renovated
and 104 new hospitals built since 1994, when the region
decided to increase the annual budget for health care from 13
million to 15 million yuan (1.8 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The region has also invested 26 million yuan (3.3 million U.S.
dollars) in the construction of family planning stations, building
30 new stations and upgrading 99 others.
</P>
<P>
About 90 medical projects at the county level, jointly
sponsored by the central and local governments, have begun
operation with funding of 16 million yuan (about 2 million
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
