<HEADLINE> Overseas Investors Encouraged to Buy Public Utilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, November 20 (Xinhua) --Shandong, a relatively developed
coastal province in east China, plans to transfer management of
local public utilities like heating, water, and garbage disposal
to overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of local government's efforts to open wider to
the outside world and to have multi-purpose forms of public
ownership, vice-governor Du Shicheng said today.
</P>
<P>
Forty projects have been listed by the local government for the
transfer of public utility rights, which are valued at 2.3 billion
yuan. They hope to be paid some four billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
And this is just the beginning, Du says the province plans to
have more transfers in future. It has 1,200 public utilities, with
assets worth nearly 78 billion yuan. Shandong has 48 cities.
</P>
<P>
It has a water supply of 2.2 billion cu.m., a 94-percent
availability of running water, 6.2 million sq.m. of heated
buildings, and 78 percent of its urban families have gas.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, the province plans to extend its urbanization rate to
50 percent or more, and increase the number of roads, water, gas,
heating, and power supplies, and telecommunications.  
</P>
</TEXT>
