<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Province Provides Better Services For Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, November 20 (Xinhua) -- China's northernmost province
of Heilongjiang has achieved marked progress in providing better
services for its elderly.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that by the year 2000, the people in the
province over 60 years old will rise to 10 percent from the
current 9.2 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang Province first introduced an old-age insurance
system for urban and rural areas in the early 1990s. So far, 3.63
million enterprise workers have participated in the system, with
total insurance premiums valued at 16.3 billion yuan (about 1.97
billion U.S. dollars). One million retired workers have received
old-age pensions valued at 14.7 billion yuan (about 1.79 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
At present, the old-age insurance system has been introduced in
85 percent of the province's rural areas, attracting 3.4 million
farmers or 43 percent of the total rural population.
</P>
<P>
Most cities in the province have joined efforts to provide
better services for the elderly, and have worked out regulations
on giving special rights for old people to enjoy free or
preferential treatment when traveling by bus, visiting local
doctors and shopping.
</P>
<P>
Some cities have set up factories to build facilities
especially for retired people.
</P>
<P>
Harbin, capital of the province, has seven such factories,
which have provided more than 50 million yuan (about 6.04 billion
U.S. dollars) in services for the elderly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
