<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 08:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Plans to Employ More Palestinian Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Israel has approved a new
plan to employ more Palestinian workers to replace foreign ones
in a bid to buffer the Israeli economy from destabilizing
fluctuations resulting from prolonged closures.
</P>
<P>
Under the new plan, Palestinian laborers will be given
special status that will allow them to return to their jobs in
Israel even after a closure is imposed, according to Yaacov Or,
coordinator of Israeli government activities in the territories.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli employers will be required to undertake to
collect and return the workers from the border crossings and, if
needed, provide the Palestinian workers with sleeping
arrangements, he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, Israeli employers have increasingly
preferred foreign workers to Palestinians, even if the Arabs work
for lower wages, because closures imposed by Israel for security
reasons make the employers difficult to depend on the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the Palestinian territories were closed off for over
100 days. Israel again imposed a total closure on the Palestinian
territories in July 30 this year after suicide bombings in
Jerusalem killed 18 people and wounded 151 others.
</P>
<P>
At its peak in the late 1980s, the Palestinian labor force in
Israel numbered over 100,000. Today, there are about 50,000
Palestinians working legally in Israel, with an estimated 40,000
more sneaking in without permits, according to Labor and Social
Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Foreign workers in Israel currently stand at 150,000 to
200,000, half of whom are illegal laborers.
</P>
<P>
At present, work permits are issued only to married
Palestinian males over 24, who have undergone a check by both
Israeli and Palestinian security authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cervix Cancer Rampant in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian health
officials have warned women to be careful in choosing male
partners so as to escape the attack of cervix cancer.
</P>
<P>
One alarming figure indicated that more than 60 percent of
female patients at Ocean Road Hospital in the capital of Dar es
Salaam have contracted cervix cancer.
</P>
<P>
President of the Tanzania Oncology Women Association (TOWA),
Dr Hulda Lugoe, told reporters yesterday in the city that most of
the affected by the disease were productive women, aged between
25 to 35 years of age.
</P>
<P>
Lugoe, who was briefing reporters Wednesday before the opening
of a two-day workshop of the association, said immoral sexual
behavior was the prime cause of the disease.
</P>
<P>
She said girls aged between 12 and 20 who has many sexual
partners are vulnerable to the disease which has claimed a number
of women's lives in most Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
The TOWA president cautioned girls to be discreet in choosing
male partners.
</P>
<P>
Teenage marriages also exposed girls to greater risk of being
affected by the cancer, she said.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that early treatment was vital if the affected
woman is to be cured from the disease. Cervix cancer has four
stages, she said. Patients in the stage one and stage two are
curable while those in the rest stages have to face death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
