<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Circumcision Spreads HIV in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Undisinfected knife used in
circumcisions have spread HIV virus in eastern Uganda, The New
Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Richard Oketch, the medical officer of Kapchorwa District,
eastern Uganda, told local councillors and department heads at a
meeting in the district Tuesday that he received a report saying
some people circumcised in the district have died of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Oketch told the officials that other people circumcised by the
same operator in the same year have shown the signs of the
existence of the virus. But he declined to reveal the name of the
infected.
</P>
<P>
"This is confidential, if I mention the place affected, people
might fear and they will not give us the information we want
during our research," he added.
</P>
<P>
A medical team will begin a two-month investigation to prove
the allegation, Oketch said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the spreading of the virus to using one knife in
operations for several people and not washing hands before the
operation.
</P>
<P>
Circumcision is a traditional ceremony for young people
reaching adult age in uganda. But in recent years, more and more
young people refused the operation, especially in urban areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Outbreak of Cholera Warned in Tanzanian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Dar es Salaam City
Commission (DCC) health officials have expressed alarm over the
resurfacing of cholera in the city, which has claimed 192 lives
over the past 10 months.
</P>
<P>
The city has announced stern measures to control the epidemic,
including a total ban on open air food vendors.
</P>
<P>
The DCC's Commissioner for Health Dr Job Laiser told reporters
Wednesday that 53 new cases were admitted to various centers in
the city in the past two days bringing the number of city
residents who have contracted the disease to 5,398.
</P>
<P>
Laiser said the government has spent more than 216 million
Shillings (about 350,000 US Dollars) for the affected.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner cautioned residents to observe hygiene,
saying that the killer disease was basically caused by negligence
of health rules.
</P>
<P>
He ordered a complete ban on the sale of food by street
vendors as well as roadside chips, meat and fish rosters, fruit
and juice sellers.
</P>
<P>
Funeral ceremonies where food and drinks are prepared had also
been restricted, while unnecessary gatherings and festivals would
also be discouraged to control the spread of the easily
communicable disease, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, private hospitals in the city has been cautioned
against admitting cholera patients since there are special
centers isolated for treating any reported cases, he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Laiser said due to increased number of new cases, the city
commission has re-opened some of its former emergency centers
which were closed.
</P>
<P>
He said more emergency centers will be opened depending on the
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat in Good Health: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Despite all the rumors
about failing health of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, Western
and Arab intelligence sources believe Arafat is in good health,
The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the unnamed sources as saying that Arafat only
suffers from exhaustion as a result of overwork and not from
degenerative diseases such as Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
Arafat reportedly often works up to 20 hours a day and this
has exacerbated the effects of his injuries in the 1992 plane
crash in Libya.
</P>
<P>
"We have looked very carefully at Arafat and we can't find
anything more than he is getting older and works himself to the
bone," a United States congressional staffer with access to
intelligence information was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian National Authority (PNA) source with frequent
access to Arafat agreed to this assessment. "When he is tired,
you find that his lips shake uncontrollably. But when he is
rested, he responds and looks like any other normal person," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Arafat has resisted pleas from his confidants
to rest more and insisted he must maintain control over all
details affecting the PNA. He confirmed that, as a result of
exhaustion, Arafat felt faint and was hospitalized over the past
six weeks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, 68, rejected Wednesday the rumors about the
deterioration of his health, saying he was "feeling well and in
good health in spite of all the mass media propaganda against my
health."
</P>
<P>
The rumors about Arafat's health first surfaced late
September when Egyptian officials disclosed that he fainted at
the conference of foreign ministers of Arab League. Some cited
television pictures of Arafat's quivering lower lips and fingers
during public appearances as evidence that he is suffering from
Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
In another report, The Jerusalem Post revealed that Arafat's
health was one of the topics discussed by Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Jordanian King Hussein when they met in
Britain's Ascot Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The report said King Hussein was particularly concerned about
"the post-Arafat era," implying that the line of succession
within the PNA was unclear and that Arafat's disability or
departure from the political scene would cause instability, if
not dissension and unrest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
