<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wage Increase Rate Down in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The rate of salary increments
has recorded a consistent downward trend since 1995 in Kenya, the
Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The remuneration increase for the coming 12 months may be even
lower, according to a survey by Price Waterhouse.
</P>
<P>
The survey, titled "The Kenya Salary Survey-1997", indicated
that the 1997 increments were lower than projected in the 1996's
survey after having sampled 123 companies in the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
Salary rose 13 percent for management staff and 14 percent for
support staff this year, compared with 14 percent for the
managers and 16 percent for the support staff in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 hike was just slightly above the inflation rate of
approximately 12 percent over the same period, said the survey.
</P>
<P>
"On average, the whole remuneration increments are falling.
This is an indication that organizations are growing slower and,
are, therefore, not able to sustain increments above inflation,"
said the survey.
</P>
<P>
The organizations surveyed are classified into 10 groups,
among them the banking and finance sectors ranked as the highest
paying.
</P>
<P>
The hospitals are the lowest paying sectors according to the
survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
