<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Better Party Ties With S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Vice-President Godfrey
Miyanda has said that the Zambian ruling Movement for Multi-party
Democracy (MMD) would like to strengthen relations with its South
African counterpart, Times of Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
This good will was expressed here Wednesday by Miyanda while
receiving South African High Commissioner Walter Thabethe.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda said that closer relations between the MMD and the
African National Congress (ANC) can encourage better
understanding between the governments of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
While the Zambian government appreciated that Zambia's former
ruling party the United National Independence Party (UNIP) has
closer ties with the ANC, Miyanda stressed, there is no harm in
the South African ruling party fostering a new friendship with
the MMD.
</P>
<P>
He said the MMD respects the traditional friendship that
exists between the UNIP and the ANC and will never insist on its
termination, but hoped that this will not deter relations between
the two governments.
</P>
<P>
The friendship between the ANC and the UNIP, which is led by
former President Kenneth Kaunda and now Zambia's biggest
opposition party, has began since Zambia won its independence and
gave considerable support for the ANC's struggle against the
racial segregation and the domination of the minority white
settlers in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Zambian vice-president also called for
solutions to level the trade imbalance in favor of South Africa
to improve trade relations between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Zambian has always been complaining that South Africa has
man-made barriers to bar Zambian goods from entering its market
while dumping its own heavily subsidized manufactured goods into
the landlocked country.
</P>
<P>
On his part, the South African diplomat said the South African
government is preparing to address the trade issue between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
He assured Miyanda that his country will open up its market to
allow Zambia goods to be exported there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
