<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Power Stations Work Well in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- China's two nuclear power
stations at Qinshan and Daya Bay have exceeded international safety
standards in most indices, according to a conference sponsored by
the China Nuclear Society in Changsha, capital of Hunan province.
</P>
<P>
The Qinshan Nuclear Power Station is located in Zhejiang
province and the Daya Bay in Guangdong province, next to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Exposure to radiation by workers is 0.79 units at Qinshan and
0.52 units at Daya Bay. The world average level is 1.51.
</P>
<P>
Qinshan and Daya Bay have greatly eased the energy shortage in
China and provide 6 percent and 20 percent of the electricity in
their provinces, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Daya Bay is expected to be able to provide a steady power
supply for Hong Kong for east 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Ninety percent of its investment, 4 billion US dollars, came
from overseas. Its annual power output has been around 700 million
US dollars, and statistics show that Daya Bay has repaid 40
percent of its overseas loans.
</P>
<P>
Daya Bay also has helped China cut its annual coal consumption
by six million tons, and a French nuclear specialist said that
this may be the station's most important contribution to the
environment.
</P>
<P>
China also imported more than 400 relevant programs and
softwares from overseas and has set up some nuclear power research
institutions such as the Sichuan Nuclear Power Base.
</P>
<P>
Several other nuclear power stations are under construction
along China's east coast, which is energy-deficient, according to
Zheng Qingyun, a senior official with the China National Nuclear
Corp.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, UK Reject Nigeria's Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
expressed concern over its loss of foreign exchange earnings
arising from the failure of its exports to meet the World Trade
Organization (WTO) standards.
</P>
<P>
A total of 79 consignments exported from Nigeria to the United
States were said to have been rejected last year on the ground of
contamination, decomposition and other U.S. Import Act
violations, the Daily Champion reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian exports were also rejected in Britain and other
European countries, and the loss of huge sum of money to the
development was worrisome, the newspaper said, quoting Suleman
Sani, permanent secretary in the Federal Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
"While it may be reasonable to suspect that the exports were
totally ignorant of the relevant regulations, it must be stressed
that such ignorance and lack of knowledge could no longer be
justified," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, some of the rejections may be due to
deliberate ploys by developed countries to suppress competing
export products from developing countries.
</P>
<P>
According to former head of state Muhamadu Buhari, this has
become crucial especially at the present time when the nation is
desperately trying to diversify its sources of foreign exchange
earnings to reduce over-dependence on oil.  
</P>
</TEXT>
