<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM: Sectarianism Blocks Anti-Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri has said that political and sectarian influence on the
country's civil service is blocking the campaign against
corruption and inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
Most top civil service positions are occupied by people with
strong attachment to sectarian politics, who are rarely selected
on the basis of their qualifications, local newspaper Daily Star
today quoted Hariri as saying Wednesday at a meeting entitled
"Corruption and Means of Combating It."
</P>
<P>
He said that public administration has been reunited after
Lebanese civil war ended in 1990, but many of those involved in
sectarian and partisan practices during the war are still
occupying administrative positions.
</P>
<P>
Hariri called on all parties and organizations to give the
existing supervisory bodies political and technical support to
allow them to perform their duties.
</P>
<P>
Administrative modernization or hiring new human resources will
be the solution to the problems, according to Hariri.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan of administration modernization, Lebanon will
start to employ for its civil service professionals without
political and sectarian affiliation and train the middle and lower
administrators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
