<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Ready to Evacuate Workers in Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
affirmed that it is ready to extend assistance and promptly
evacuate, if necessary, Filipinos in the Middle East who may be
affected by the U.S.-Iraq conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency today quoted Overseas Workers
Welfare Administration (OWWA) chief Wilhelm Soriano as saying that
the OWWA stands ready to implement together with the Department of
Foreign Affairs and the Department of Labor and Employment a
contingency plan to pull the Filipinos out of the areas around
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and the United States are currently engaged in a standoff
over Iraq's expulsion of American experts who are members of the
United Nations arms inspection team in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Soriano, however, said that the situation in the Middle East
has so far remained stable and that "there are no signs of
disturbing developments in the Gulf countries."
</P>
<P>
The Filipinos in the region, he added, "are in fact unperturbed
with the current news on the Iraq-U.S. standoff."
</P>
<P>
The Department of Foreign Affairs said its various diplomatic
posts are closely monitoring developments in the Gulf region and
would act promptly in assisting and evacuating Filipino overseas
workers there should open hostilities become imminent.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government announced today that it would
unconditionally accept the return of U.N. arms inspectors
including the Americans.
</P>
