<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Hydro-Electric Power Resources (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- This is the time for China to
exploit its hydro-electric power resources, and a major step was
taken on October 28 when the Yellow River was dammed for the
construction of the Xiaolangdi water control project in Henan
Province.
</P>
<P>
six 300,000-kw generators will be installed at Xiaolangdi and
they will generate 5.1 billion kwh of electricity a year
when the project is completed.
</P>
<P>
Then, on November 8, damming of China's longest Yangtze River
for the construction of the multi-purpose dam at the Three Gorges
was completed. The dam will be the biggest of its kind in the
world, and its 26 generators will be able to generate 84.6 billion
kwh of electricity a year, 13 billion kwh more than the
Itaipu power station in South America, presently the world's
largest.
</P>
<P>
In a recent speech, Premier Li Peng called for increasing
hydro-electric power's share of the country's power from
25 percent now to 30 percent by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the Chinese Government places greater
importance on developing hydro-electric power resources has
brought opportunities for China's minor rivers like the Lancang in
the southwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
