<HEADLINE> Iraq Agrees on UN Arms Inspectors' Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Iraq agreed to allow all
U.N. weapons inspectors to return to the country from Thursday,
according to a joint statement with Russia released here today.
</P>
<P>
The statement, which paved the way to solve the U.N.-Iraqi
crisis through political and diplomatic means, said Iraq agreed to
allow all the inspectors to return to work from November 20.
</P>
<P>
Russia is expected to do all it can to urge the U.N. to lift up
the sanctions imposed on Iraq as soon as possible if Iraq
fulfills all the resolutions of the U.N. Security Council, said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
"The special committee should raise its working efficiency, and
the sovereignty and security of Iraq should be respected," the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tarik Aziz visited Moscow between November 18-19. Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and Iraqi President Saddam Hussein had
also exchanged views with letters on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The crisis occurred when Iraq decided to expel U.S. arms
inspectors out of the country on October 29. 
</P>
