<HEADLINE> Writers, Economists Discuss China's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- China's most renowned writers
and economists gathered here today to discuss their
responsibilities in the country's future.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time members from literary and economic
circles of China jointly held a forum on issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
They said economists and writers have different perspectives
when observing the society, but they share responsibility for building
a prosperous China.
</P>
<P>
The writers said economists should pay more attention to ethics
when submitting reform suggestions to the government, while
economists urged writers to go out of their studies and
learn more from the reality.
</P>
<P>
"The dialogue will help build a rational society with good
ethics and economic miracles," said economist Fan Gang.
</P>
<P>
Chinese literature's golden period occurred in the early 1980s
with many masterpieces pushing forward reform and progress, critics
say. But since the late 1980s, serious literature has suffered
because of commercial considerations.
</P>
<P>
Many readers have been lured away from reading good literature
by imported movies and VCDs, and some writers have turned to
popular fiction to make money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
