<HEADLINE> Pak Court Directs President Not to OK Contempt Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of
Pakistan today directed the president not to assent to an amended
contempt law passed by the two houses of the Parliament on
Tuesday, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
The apex court passed an interim order this morning, stating
that in case the president assents to the bill, it will stand
suspended, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the two houses of the Parliament passed the amended
contempt law tending to give protection to Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif in the ongoing contempt case against him in the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
The amended law, which provided for an intra-court appeal
before a "larger bench consisting of all the remaining available
judges of the court within the country," has been submitted to
President Farooq Leghari for signing.
</P>
<P>
Under the Constitution of Pakistan, Leghari has 30 days to
decide whether to assent to the bill.
</P>
<P>
Sharif Wednesday urged the president to sign the bill into law
to end the prevailing political crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Earlier the bill is signed, sooner the crisis will come to an
end," Sharif said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
