<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Emigration Drops in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Fewer people emigrated
from South Africa in July 1997 while more people came in, the
Central Statistics Service (CSS) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the month, the number of self-declared emigrants was 636, a
24 percent decline compared with July 1996, CSS said.
</P>
<P>
The number of professionals, semi-professionals and
technicians who reported that they were emigrating was 144 while
the corresponding number who immigrated into South Africa was 60.
</P>
<P>
The gap between emigration and immigration, though still
there, is narrowing.
</P>
<P>
In July this year, the number of immigrants was 412, an
increase of 10 percent compared with July 1996.
</P>
<P>
The leading source countries of immigration in July were
Britain (14 percent), India (8 percent) and Germany (5 percent),
while the leading destinations of emigration were Britain (27
percent), New Zealand (16 percent), the United States (12
percent), Australia (11 percent), Namibia (7 percent) and Canada
(5 percent).
</P>
<P>
The historical trends in the number of immigrants and
self-declared emigrants showed that the number of immigrants has
never again exceeded the number of emigrants ever since 1993.
</P>
<P>
The gap narrowed in the second half of 1994 and again in the
last quarter of 1996. It seemed to be further narrowing this
year.
</P>
<P>
South Africa suffered when at one hand, numerous professionals
flocked from the country and at the other hand, poorly-educated
illegal immigrants, estimated at millions in number, flooded in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
