<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's First Xia-Chinese Dictionary Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- China has published the
world's first Xia-Chinese dictionary, blazing a new trail into the
mystery of the ancient Western Xia Kingdom, according to the
overseas edition of today's "People's Daily."
</P>
<P>
Scholars said the language of the Western Xia is one of the
most difficult in the world. Many mysteries remain about the
regime and its people because only a few people could understand
the language.
</P>
<P>
The language, created by the Dangxiang nationality nearly 1,000
years ago, disappeared along with the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Experts did not rediscover the language until the beginning of
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
Li Fanwen, a 65-year-old professor who edited the dictionary,
has researched the language in Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region since
1960.
</P>
<P>
The dictionary, containing more than 6,000 ancient Western Xia
words, provides readers with explanations in both Chinese and
English. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
