<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Seek Foreign Partners for Major Environment Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- China's top industrial city of
Shanghai has announced plans to initiate a number of joint ventures to
deal with major environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
Lu Shuping, Director of Shanghai's Bureau of Environmental
Protection, said here at the "97 China Environment Forum" that
stress for Sino-foreign cooperation would put on the control of
sulfur dioxide air pollution and noise pollution, toxic waste
disposal, clean production methods and large environmental
protection ventures.
</P>
<P>
Lu said her city has launched pollution control projects with
Great Britain, Australia, Japan, Norway, Denmark, the Netherlands
and some international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The official said Shanghai's environmental targets for 2000
include promotion of clean production, a 10 percent decrease in
waste discharge using 1985 as a base year, control of air
pollution and establishment of an environmental protection
framework.
</P>
<P>
She said the city will build two large domestic waste disposal
plants and move more polluting enterprises out of urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's industrial output accounts for 11.9 percent of the
national total and it has spent 6 billion yuan (720 million
U.S. dollars) for industrial pollution control projects in the
last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The "97 China Environment Forum" is the first high-level
international environmental forum ever held in China. President
Jiang Zemin sent a congratulatory message to the forum and Premier
Li Peng met with representatives of foreign participants before
the forum opened Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
