<HEADLINE> Ecology of Yangtze River's Upper Reaches Protected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Sichuan Province has committed
its resources to improving the ecology in the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River to protect the region's biodiversity and conserve
water.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to the river valley's ecology and
forest protection, said officials with the Provincial
Forestry Department.
</P>
<P>
The province in southwestern China has planted more than 2.67
hectares of trees, raising the forest coverage rate to 20.35
percent from 9 percent in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Soil erosion remains a serious problem because of
deforestation, improper land development, mining practices and
road construction, experts say.
</P>
<P>
The province's land area affected by soil erosion has been
estimated at 200,000 square kilometers, accounting for 41 percent
of the province's coverage.
</P>
<P>
To protect forests, the government has revised the rural energy
structure to reduce the burning of wood. To date, 36 of the
province's 117 counties have realized electrification.
</P>
<P>
Plans of the Provincial Forestry Department estimate that
within the next three years the forest coverage rate is expected
to be raised to 30 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
