<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly in Chinese City Receive Special Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Lin Mingbo, 79, said he
admires the 90-year-old people who swim during the winter and do
morning exercises.
</P>
<P>
Shantou, a city in southern China's Guangdong Province, now has
42 elders 100 or older. People over 60 number 380,000, or 9.45
percent of the city's population.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the number of old people adds color to the
city's spare-time activities, local residents say.
</P>
<P>
Early in the morning, hundreds of the elderly come to the
city's coastal road for morning exercise, which has become a
famous scene in the city.
</P>
<P>
The elderly use musical instruments donated by various social
groups, and drink free tea and other drinks.
</P>
<P>
Lin said the local government allocates regular subsidies for
the elderly, and they can visit parks and other public facilities
free of charge.
</P>
<P>
Lin said, in Shantou those who do not respect the elders will
be criticized by others. "We now live a comfortable life, and We
are just concerned about our health," he said.
</P>
<P>
Most residents find that sending parents to "Homes for the
Elderly" is inconceivable. They take care of their own parents,
though they are busy with work.
</P>
<P>
To better serve the elderly, Shantou established a working
committee for senior citizens and an elders' fund 10 years ago. At
present, organizations for the elderly have been set up and
the elderly colleges are popular.
</P>
<P>
Local government often organizes various activities to enrich
old people's lives and to boost their morale.  
</P>
</TEXT>
