<HEADLINE> Private Economy in Industrial Base Makes Headway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Shenyang, capital city of
northeast China's Liaoning province, the country's traditional
industrial base, has approved 209,000 private enterprises by the
end of August, an increase of 1.2-fold over the figure of 1992.
</P>
<P>
For a long time, the public sector has occupied the absolute
predominance in the city's economy. And the heavy industrial base
of Shenyang owns an integrated industrial system and a group of
state-owned enterprises, said Mu Suixin, mayor of the city.
</P>
<P>
However, the approved private enterprises have involved a total
registered capital of 11.8 billion yuan (1.47 billion US
dollars), 14.7 times more than that of 1992, which show that the
sector has received great progress in the past five years, said Mu.
</P>
<P>
And the city had witnessed a total business volume of 40.8
billion yuan (5.1 billion US dollars) from the service industry by
the end of August.
</P>
<P>
The private enterprises are equal to share the preferential
policies like state-owned enterprises and Sino-foreign joint
ventures, co-operative enterprises and wholely foreign-funded
companies, according to Mu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
