<HEADLINE> China's Largest Natural Gas Plant Nears Completion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, November 20 (Xinhua) -- China's largest natural gas
purification plant has been completed and will soon be put into
service in northwestern China's Changqing Gas Field.
</P>
<P>
The Changqing Gas Field has been operating since the first
high-yield gas well was sunk on June 22, 1989. The field is
situated in the Erdos Basin which sits on the juncture of Shaanxi,
Gansu and Shanxi provinces, and Ningxia Hui and Inner Mongolia
autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
The No. 1 gas purification plant, with an annual capacity of
1.8 billion cubic meters of gas, is north of the county seat of
Jingbian in northern Shaanxi Province. The plant is considered a
key gas field exploration.
</P>
<P>
The plant began construction in April, 1996. The first phase
was completed in 14 months with the installation of three sets of
gas purification equipment and completion of necessary support
facilities at a cost of more than 300 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
For the second stage construction, the plant will add two more
sets of gas purification equipment. When the plant is finished, it
will be able to treat three billion cubic meters of gas a year,
according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
Technology used in the gas purification process was imported
from the Honewell Company of Australia. Indexes of various harmful
particles in the treated gas reportedly are lower than China's
state-set standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
