<HEADLINE> China's Ambassador Elaborates Position on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Ambassador Sha Zukang at
China's permanent mission in Geneva today elaborated his country's
position at a ministerial meeting meant to seek a diplomatic
solution to the three-week-long Iraq weapons inspection crisis.
</P>
<P>
"As the President of the Security Council for the current
month," Sha said, "since the beginning of the crisis, China has,
in the spirit of fairness and neutrality, been calling upon all
the parties concerned to adopt a sober and restrained approach."
</P>
<P>
As representative of the Chinese Foreign Minister, Sha took
part in the two-hour meeting, also attended by British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine,
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov and U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
"We firmly stand for a settlement through dialogue and
cooperation to avoid escalation of the crisis, especially armed
conflicts," Sha said. "We are pleased to note that all parties
present here share the wish to resolve the dispute through
diplomatic channels."
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that all parties concerned would take a flexible
and constructive approach in seeking an earliest possible solution
acceptable to all. 
</P>
