<HEADLINE> Polder Reclamation to Draw More Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Jiangsu, a densely populated
province in eastern China, is trying to attract overseas
investment for shore-land development.
</P>
<P>
The province's 953.9-kilometer-long coastline with 650,000
hectares of reclaimable land along the sea makes it a valuable
resource. The province plans to reclaim 66,700 ha. by 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Kaitao, the official in charge of the project,
reclaiming land from the sea is expensive. The transformation of
the projected area requires an investment of two billion yuan (240
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Li said that the construction of one kilometer of sea wall
would cost two million yuan and another 30,000 yuan for each
hectare of shore-land would be required for necessary improvements.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996 when Jiangsu applied for loans from the World Bank,
the province has been seeking joint cooperation with large
overseas investors, such as Shell Oil Co. to develop planting,
breeding and storage on the reclaimed land. So far, the province
has commitments for 10 million U.S. dollars in investment.
</P>
<P>
In another development, many overseas investors have expressed
interest in a multi-functional venture which would integrate the
developments of high-efficiency farming, industry, transportation,
port trade and seashore tourism into one.  
</P>
</TEXT>
