<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gansu Tapping Water, Thermal Power Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, November 20 (Xinhua) -- A high-voltage power
transmission grid has taken shape in northwestern China thanks to
efforts by Gansu Province in tapping hydro-power and thermal power
resources.
</P>
<P>
The province has built more than 450 hydro-power plants with an
installed generating capacity of 2.3 million kilowatts (kw), which
function as the hub of the northwestern grid, according to the
Gansu Electric Power Administration.
</P>
<P>
Called by some the "small Three Gorges Project," the Daxia
Hydro-power Plant will be joined by the Xiaoxia and Wujin Gorge
plants now under construction for an installed generating capacity
of 700,000 kw.
</P>
<P>
Gansu also has joined with Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region to
build the Jishixia Project and with Qinghai Province in
constructing the Heishanxia Project.
</P>
<P>
Gansu has a hydroelectric potential of 11.1 million kw, most
on the Yellow River. From Jishixia to Heishanxia on the river, the
water drop of 820 meters makes it possible to construct ten large-
or medium-size hydro-power plants with an installed generating
capacity of 4.18 million kw.
</P>
<P>
Gansu's Jingyuan Thermal Power Plant is in its second phase
and will join five other thermal power plants with an installed
generating capacity of 2.6 million kw.
</P>
<P>
Among them, with a joint investment of 2.8 billion yuan (about
340 million U.S. dollars), the second phase of Jingyuan Plant has
been funded by Gansu Electric Power Administration and a United
States firm.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, Gansu expects to finish the
Pingliang Thermal Power Plant with an installed generating
capacity of 1.2 million kw. Zhangye Thermal Power Plant, which has
an installed generating capacity of 250,000 kw, is in its first
phase. The province also is revamping the Xigu Thermal Power Plant
and expanding the Lianchen Thermal Power Plant.
</P>
<P>
According to the provincial administration, Gansu is striving
to increase its installed generating capacity by 2.18 million kw
by the end of the century through attracting investment from both
home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Also, Gansu will try to meet its ever-increasing demand for
power in the first five years of the next century to achieve the
goal of maintaining stable development in its power industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
