<HEADLINE> Malaria Is Tanzania's No.1 Baby Killer, WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaria, acute
respiratory infection, diarrhea, anemia and malnutrition account
for more than two thirds of deaths in children below the age of
five in Tanzania, the World Health Organization has said.
</P>
<P>
The WHO Clinical Instructor for Tanzania Office, Dr Leslie
Ngalula, said here Wednesday that the diseases are the major
cause of high hospital attendance and admissions.
</P>
<P>
"But these diseases do not get wide coverage in the media like
accidents," Ngalula said.
</P>
<P>
Records indicate that 115 children under five years age die
out of every 1,000 in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the Ministry of Health, in collaboration with WHO,
UNICEF and the World Bank, has developed an integrated management
of childhood illness (MCI) strategy.
</P>
<P>
This approach is intended to reduce child mortality and
morbidity associated with the major diseases.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, Zambia and Uganda have been picked as MCI pilot
projects to spearhead its introduction.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania introduced the MCI training program to health workers
who are stationed at dispensaries and health centers in seven
district last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
