<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Doctors Treat Mammary Cancer with New Method </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Doctors in Shanghai say that
electro-chemotherapy is very effective in treating patients in the
late stages of mammary cancer.
</P>
<P>
In 1992 doctors at Shanghai Dongfang Mastopathy Hospital (SDMH)
began to adopt electro-chemotherapy, which was developed by the
Atomic Energy Research Institute of China.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Yuan Yongxi, together with three other doctors in SDMH,
applied electro-chemotherapy to 30 cancer patients from 26 to 75
years old whose tumors were fist-size or bigger. All had been
diagnosed as unsuitable for surgery.
</P>
<P>
Among the 30 patients treated, 15 are symptom-free and living a
normal life and 10 say they are feeling much better. To doctors'
surprise, all patients' tumors showed a tendency to shrink, some
by half, others by two-thirds and some disappeared. The curative
effects of electro-chemotherapy reached 83 percent.
</P>
<P>
The way that electric-chemotherapy works is to disturb the
surrounding environment of the cancer cells so as to alter them
with direct and pulsating currents, according to the doctors.
</P>
<P>
Three-year clinical experiments have proved
electro-chemotherapy is a safe therapy without side-effects,
doctors said, and is particularly suitable for those suffering
mammary cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Gives Loan for Reform in Bangladeshi Silk Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) has approved
a interest-free credit of 11.35 million U.S. dollars for a project
to revitalize Bangladesh's silk production, a WB press release
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The silk development project will support the government's
decision to deregulate silk production and establish an autonomous
non-profit body called the Bangladesh Silk Foundation, which will
take over some of the commercial responsibilities of the
Bangladesh Silk Board.
</P>
<P>
The project is the first phase of a long-term program to
transform Bangladesh's seri-culture into a technically up-to-date
sector with a reputation for quality in world markets.
</P>
<P>
The newly-created Silk Foundation, with representatives of
small-scale silk producers, NGOs, private financial institutions,
garment manufacturers, and the government on its board, will be in
charge of project implementation, the release stated.
</P>
<P>
The foundation's primary objective is to assist in introducing
improved technology, bringing silk research and extension
activities under majority control of the stake-holders, and it
will also work to improve the investment climate and serve as a
"think-tank" to advise the government on policy options, it added.
</P>
<P>
The project's estimated total cost is about 13 million dollars
of which the government will contribute 1.21 million.
</P>
<P>
When the project is implemented, silkworm rearers' daily
earnings are expected to triple over the project period and
increased employment opportunities are expected in all areas of
silk production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
