<HEADLINE> Protective Development of Tourist Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Quanzhou, a historic city on
the ancient "Silk Road," is reconstructing temples and expanding
museums to attract more tourists.
</P>
<P>
Quanzhou, a small city in southeast China's Fujian Province,
boasts more than 1,760 registered sites of historic
interests. Since 1994, it has been one of the ten top tourist
destinations in China.
</P>
<P>
Since the city was designated a "Famous Historic and Cultural
City," Quanzhou has spent more than 200 million yuan (24 million
U.S. dollars) in renovating more than 300 Buddhist
temples, many internationally known, and other projects.
</P>
<P>
The city has also spent money on the expansion of numerous
museums including the history of overseas traffic and overseas
Chinese, relations with Taiwan, pottery art and historical figures.
</P>
<P>
In the Quanzhou Overseas Communications Museum, visitors can
see oceangoing ships made in the Song Dynasty (960-1279), stone
carvings in Arabic and religious stone statues of Hindus and
Christians.
</P>
<P>
The province also has improved facilities for tourists at
scenic mountains and beaches such as Mount Qingyuan, Zimao and
Jiuri, and Chongwu Beach.  
</P>
