<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Can Sustain 6-7 Percent Fiscal Deficit: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 20 (Xinhua) -- India can easily sustain a
fiscal deficit of 6-7 percent if its economy grows at 7 percent of
the GDP annually, a local newspaper "Business Standard" quoted a
senior official as saying today.
</P>
<P>
"There is no sacrosanct number in case of fiscal deficit. All
this talk that 4 percent is the ideal fiscal deficit is bunkum, a
myth," said Arjun Sengupta, member of the Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
According to him, India's economic fundamentals were "never so
good as today" and it can comfortably grow at 8 percent of the GDP
"if you don't make a mistake."
</P>
<P>
Yet he warned that a crisis could be brewing if nothing was
done to boost exports. "It is unbelievable that our exports have
been allowed to come down to the current rate of 2 percent. It is
perfectly possible that our economy will face a tremendous crisis
in the next weeks," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sengupta attributed the poor health of industry to the
overcapacities created in many sectors over the past two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
