<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manipulators Create Havoc in Developing Countries: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim said today currency traders manipulating
regional currencies are opportunists who took advantage of a flaw
in the economic system and created havoc in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"For that reason, Malaysia has called for transparency in
currency trading ... the present system was without rules and
regulations," Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, said at a
function here.
</P>
<P>
He said that industrialized countries are not keen for
transparency in currency trading because the manipulators and
speculators who caused havoc in regional markets are from the rich
and powerful industrial countries.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, Thailand, Indonesia, the Philippines and even
Singapore have been seriously affected by the current allegedly
manipulated financial crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia was not as badly affected as Thailand because
its ruling coalition National Front was strong and Malaysia was
also fortunate for not having to resort to high borrowings and
funding to bail out its economy like Thailand and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has committed 1 billion U.S. dollars each to Thailand
and Indonesia to help their economies as well as to ensure there
would not be any contagion effect.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said Malaysia would be able to overcome the regional
financial and economic crisis if it was able to manage the economy
well.
</P>
<P>
"We need to remain competitive and strengthen economic
fundamentals," he said, adding this would mean having a high rate
of savings, no wasteful expenditure, generating higher exports,
belt-tightening measures and enhancing productivity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
