<HEADLINE> Drought-Related Diseases Kill 522 in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- At least 522 people had died
by mid-November of diseases caused by a prolonged drought in
Indonesia's easternmost province of Irian Jaya, a senior official
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the House of Representatives here Wednesday, Home
Affairs Minister Yogie S. Memet said of the total victims, 430
people were from Jaya Wijaya district, 68 in Merauke and 24 in
Puncak Jaya.
</P>
<P>
Diarrhea, malaria and other diseases have been spreading in
remote villages in the province since mid August. The
drought-related diseases were threatening the lives of 90,000
people there, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
Memet said the government has sent food, drugs, drinking water
and medical assistance including those contributed by neighboring
countries to drought victims.
</P>
<P>
He also said the ongoing forest fires at several places have
damaged 167,361.83 hectares of land, of which 165.361.83 hectares
are forest land.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Forum for Environment said earlier that the
forest fires have caused a total loss of 3.15 billion U.S.
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
