<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Issues Rule China's Economy's Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- China's economic life in the
future will be swayed by six issues, according to the Beijing-based
China Economic Times.
</P>
<P>
First, the increase in redundant workers has replaced inflation
as the biggest problem from a macro-economic standpoint.
</P>
<P>
However, it can be a good news if viewed from another angle: The
country's economic restructuring and workforce streamlining have
enhanced their aggressiveness; inflation has been brought down to
acceptable level, today's China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
Second, the continuing increase of foreign reserves might not
necessarily be good news for China's economy. In a sense, it not
only makes it difficult to offset the operation of the Bank of
China, but also propels the renminbi to continue to appreciate and
cause possible trade friction.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper suggests that the State grant loans in
U.S. dollars to large enterprise groups and foreign trade
enterprises; expand the import of advanced equipment and the
lastest technology; and increase direct investment in foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
Third, the old housing system that requires State units to buy
houses for their employees as welfares encumbers the housing
industry.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, to keep China's economic growth at 9-10 percent
annually, it is necessary to increase the margin of investment at
around 15 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
Fifth, the State should encourage financial capital to merge
with industrial capital. The newspaper suggested the participation
may be more effective if banks convert the creditors' rights they
hold in those promising enterprises into rights to hold shares in
them.
</P>
<P>
Sixth, in the movement to form large enterprise groups, the
market, rather than administrative orders, should be encouraged as
motivating force. However, in some places, local government simply
force better-performing enterprises to annex ailing ones, a move
contrary to the State policy to encourage the big and healthy
enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
