<HEADLINE> Racial Advisory Board Discusses Campus Diversity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton's racial advisory board discussed the diversity of college
campuses today.
</P>
<P>
In its third meeting held at the University of Maryland, the
seven-member board heard testimony from school presidents,
academics and others, on how to make diversity work at colleges
and universities.
</P>
<P>
Board Chairman John Hope Franklin said the board did not want
to lose track of the good work under way in diversity programs by
inviting debate over affirmative action -- a formal effort to
provide increased employment and education opportunities for women
and ethnic minorities to overcome past discrimination.
</P>
<P>
University of Maryland President William Kirwan described the
loss of his school's minority scholarship program as "one of the
earliest casualties in a nationwide assault on affirmative action
programs."
</P>
<P>
Franklin did not rule out discussing affirmative action in
later sessions. He announced four more meetings at various
locations.
</P>
<P>
The board also tentatively scheduled a town hall forum in
mid-January in Atlanta. Clinton has scheduled the first meeting
on December 3 in Akron, Ohio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
