<HEADLINE> Mexico, China Agree on Investment Opportunities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, November 19 (Xinhua) -- A great potential exists
for economic cooperation between Mexico and China and the two
countries should expand mutual investment, a senior Mexican
official said today.
</P>
<P>
"We think there is a great potential for our economic relations
with China. We have just learned of the first investments of
Chinese companies in Mexico," Jaime Zabludovsky, under secretary
of Mexico's Commerce and Industrial Development told Xinhua in an
exclusive interview.
</P>
<P>
The official said Mexican and Chinese companies are to sign
agreements on investment for the construction of a textile plant
in northwestern Mexico and for agricultural and cattle breeding
projects in southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
However, the under secretary also pointed out that trade
cooperation between Mexico and China is still too small.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the joint projects, Zabludovsky said Chinese
investment in Mexico can also help China enter the markets of the
United States and Canada, partner countries of Mexico in the North
American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).
</P>
<P>
With NAFTA, Mexico has direct access to the markets of the
United States and Canada. Mexico also has free trade agreements
with Costa Rica, Venezuela, Colombia, Bolivia and Chile.
</P>
<P>
"We are currently negotiating with the rest of the hemispheric
markets and we will start negotiating with Europe next year,"
Zabludovsky asserted.
</P>
<P>
As for Mexican businessmen, they were beginning to explore the
Chinese market, the under secretary said.
</P>
<P>
Zabludovsky suggested that both countries make efforts to
increase business contacts between the investors.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo paid an official
visit to China in a bid to promote bilateral cooperation and
figure out a mechanism to enhance commerce and investment between
the two nations.
</P>
<P>
On November 30 to December 3, Chinese President Jiang Zemin is
scheduled to visit Mexico. Zabludovsky said the Mexican
government is looking forward to the visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
