<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fletcher Challenge to Enter NZ Petrol Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand company
Fletcher Challenge is to open a petrol chain throughout New
Zealand (NZ)'s North Island and plans to sell petrol by next
April.
</P>
<P>
TVNZ today quoted the company as saying that it will compete on
price and services. Initially, Fletcher Challenge will invest 75
million NZ dollars (47 million U.S. dollars) in the project, which
 will eventually cover all parts of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The move followed a similar one announced by the Australian oil
company Liberty last month, which said it could sell petrol at a
price 10 NZ cents (6.2 U.S. cents) cheaper a liter than those
pegged by the four New Zealand oil companies of BP, Mobil, Shell
and Caltex.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, Energy Minister Max Bradford expressed his
delight at the entry of new players.
</P>
<P>
"By April next year both Fletcher Challenge and Liberty will be
competing in the petrol retail market, and that will lead to more
choices and cheaper prices for consumers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since becoming energy minister late last year, Bradford has
repeatedly expressed concerns at the expensive petrol prices in
New Zealand, which are among the highest in Western nations. He
blamed the four oil companies for monopolizing the prices.
</P>
<P>
Bradford said the prospects for full competition throughout the
energy industry in New Zealand were looking good, adding that the
government was actively working to achieve the same sort of
competition in electricity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relatives to Pay Homage to Argentine Soldiers Fallen in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, November 19 (Xinhua) -- A group of relatives of
Argentine soldiers killed in the Malvinas (Falklands) War left for
the islands today to pay homage to the dead.
</P>
<P>
The group of 15 relatives and a priest will visit the cemetery
of Sarwin in the Southern Atlantic Islands, where were buried 237
Argentine soliders killed in the 1982 war between Argentina and
Britain over the sovereignty of the islands.
</P>
<P>
The visit is the first of its kind sponsored by the country's
Foreign Ministry, which is organizing other two similar trips
scheduled for January and February 1998, according to Cesar
Gonzalez Trejo, president of Argentina's Federation of War
Veterans.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said that Argentine Foreign Minister Guido
Di Tella was denied access to the islands by the British governor
of the islands, Richar Ralph, who said "Argentine officials are
not welcome here."
</P>
<P>
Though Argentina lost the war with Britain, it still claims
sovereignty over those islands.
</P>
<P>
Before the departure, the mother of one dead soldier said their
bodies must remain there as "symbols" of Argentina's sovereignty
over those islands. 
</P>
