<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland Reducing Foreign Debts by Billions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Poland's foreign debts have
been reduced by 13.9 billion U.S. dollars during the last four
years, the official statistics said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistical materials, Poland's debts have been
reduced from 47.9 billion dollars in 1993 to 34 billion dollars in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts say the main reasons for Poland's debt reduction
consist of the following three reasons:
</P>
<P>
Foreign creditors' debt has been cut by five billion dollars
since 1993; the rapid development of Poland's economy has provided
the government with more foreign reserves to pay their debts, and
current foreign reserves have reached 20 billion U.S. dollars; the
stronger U.S. dollar and weaker German mark have also helped
Poland reduce its foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, analysts point out, Poland still has to pay several
billion dollars in annual interests for its current debts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Foreign Debt Soars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic's foreign
debt has surged to 21.2 billion U.S. dollars, with the per capita
debt jumping from 822 dollars in 1993 to 2,000 dollars now, the
Czech National Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of foreign debt accounted for 43 percent of the gross
domestic product (GDP) of the country, three percent over the
internationally accepted "alarm" line, a spokesman of the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
Economists attributed the increasing debt to economic slowdown,
shortage of capital and a large deficit in foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, the country's foreign debt was at a
relatively low level because of the Czech government's effective
measures. It stood at 8.5 billion dollars in 1993.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign debt soared to 20.4 billion dollars in
1996, over the previous year's 16.5 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
