<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Thai Labor Minister Vows to Axe Alien Laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's new Labor and
Social Welfare Minister Trairong Suwannakhiri has vowed to sack
alien laborers working in Thailand as a measure to ease the
employment situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The minister has instructed the Employment Department under his
ministry to work out a master plan for the purpose within 100 days
and enable more unemployed Thais to fill the positions, according
to local newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Given the current economic situation in Thailand, the layoffs
must be immediately implemented to help those Thais in trouble,
Trairong said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The number of immigrant workers in Thailand has reached 1
million, exceeding the 600,000 estimated earlier, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the massive layoff plan against
alien workers would help re-employ more than 92,500 Thais who lost
jobs due to the country's ongoing economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government last year introduced a policy to allow
immigrant workers in the country to work legally for a period of
two years to help ease the country's temporary shortage of labor.
</P>
<P>
Currently, most alien workers in Thailand come from Thailand's
neighboring countries, like Myanmar. The new move against foreign
laborers is part of the new Thai government's efforts to re-adjust
its employment policy.
</P>
<P>
The government of Chuan Leekpai, which was sworn in on November
15, currently is also considering radical measures to streamline
its civil service workforce, including freezing staff growth and
transferring central government officials to local agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
