<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Urges Efforts to Prevent AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia had a total of 671
registered AIDS patients by the end of September, among whom 465
have died, said a communique issued today by the Yugoslav AIDS
prevention expert team.
</P>
<P>
The communique called on the whole nation to make concerted
efforts to fight AIDS, especially trying to reduce the cases of
HIV-infected children.
</P>
<P>
Among the AIDS patients in Yugoslavia, about 49 percent are
drug addicts and 16.7 percent homosexuals; there are also 18
children suffering from AIDS, among whom six have been infected
from their mothers.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that as three million children under the
age of 15 around the world are now HIV-infected, this year's World
AIDS Prevention Day on December 1 will focus on "caring for the
children living in a world with AIDS".
</P>
<P>
Some 8,500 people worldwide are newly infected with HIV each
day, among whom 1,000 are children.
</P>
<P>
The communique warned that AIDS could become the leading killer
of children under five if no effective preventive measures are
taken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
