<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Longevity County Takes Good Care of Centenarians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Bama Autonomous County of Yao
Nationality, home to 79 centenarians, has made it a daily task to
care for and protect its senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
The county's public security bureau and police stations at all
levels have given priority to centenarians in cases of robbery and
physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
Of the county's 79, 18 are men and 61 are women with the oldest
112 years old.
</P>
<P>
According to the fourth national census, by July 1, 1990, the
county had 260 people between 90 and 99, and 1,724 between 80 and
89.
</P>
<P>
The county government has passed special regulations to protect
centenarians and urged townships to set up files on them.
</P>
<P>
The county government also gives "centenarian certificates" to
those who pass 100, grants subsidies and calls on the whole
society to look after its elder citizens.
</P>
<P>
Family members of centenarians are asked to improve their
living conditions, and are not allowed to abandon or abuse their
elderly relatives.
</P>
<P>
Local governments and scientific departments have carried out
research on medical treatment and health care for the elderly
based on the lives of the Bama centenarians to explore the secrets
of longevity.
</P>
<P>
There are 5,055 homes and day-care centers for the aged and
more than 1,200 state-owned welfare homes for the elderly that
provide accommodations for more than 38,000. Some 620,000 elderly
live in 40,000 collectively owned homes for the elderly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
