<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica, Canada Sign Power Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica and Canada today
signed an agreement to pool their efforts in bringing about
rational and efficient management, supply and consumption of
electric power in Central America.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, both sides will contribute 425 million
colones (about 1.8 million U.S. dollars) for the implementation of
the project over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to strengthen reforms for the
improvement and efficiency in the supply and consumption of
electric power, as well as to expand regional cooperation and
private participation in that area.
</P>
<P>
It also aims to make good use of power generated by
hydroelectric, geothermal and thermoelectric plants in the region.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed by Costa Rica Minister of Planning
Leonardo Garnier and Canada's Ambassador here, Dan Goodleaf.
</P>
<P>
Garnier said Central American countries will make more efforts
to integrate regional electric networks so as to encourage a more
rational consumption of power.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the accord took place at a seminar on electric
power policies and cooperation among several state-run and private
companies in Central American countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
