<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SmithKline Plans Joint Venture in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- A world-renowned
pharmaceutical company is about to reveal its technology to China,
one step at a time.
</P>
<P>
SmithKline Beecham Biological Shanghai Ltd, to be a subsidiary
of SmithKline Beecham Co., is expected to open in July 1999 at a
cost of 100 million U.S. dollars, said Peter Walters, chairman of
the board of SmithKline Beecham Co..
</P>
<P>
He noted that his company is looking towards a long-term
cooperation with China, where they found a huge market.
</P>
<P>
The technology transfer will help his company expand its market
share in China, but obstacles exist because China is not yet a
member of the World Trade Organization, he added.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming joint venture has been jointly funded by Shanghai
Institute of Biological Products, China National Biological
Products Co. and SmithKline Beecham Co.. It will manufacture
several types of vaccines.
</P>
<P>
SmithKline, a world's leading health care firm, has already had
a pharmaceutical joint venture in China, called Sino-US Tianjin
SmithKline and French Laboratories Ltd, with Tianjin
Pharmaceutical Co. and Tianjin Amino Acid Corp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
