<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Allowed to Interfere in Private Enterprises in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Albania's People's Assembly,
the parliament, today passed a bill in a bid to allow governmental
interference in the privately-owned enterprises in special cases.
</P>
<P>
The supplementary provision to the constitution, which was
passed with 190 votes for, four against and two abstention after
heated debate, said that the state has the right to interfere when
a private enterprise's behavior endangers or infringes upon
citizens' interests.
</P>
<P>
The motion was submitted to the parliament by the Albanian
government.
</P>
<P>
Before that, the government was annoyed by the "VEFA" company's
rejection to its decision to send supervisors to the company,
whose illicit fund-raising had led to financial turmoils all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
The company, however, defeated the government in its appeal to
the constitutional court. The court held that the government's
decision violated the constitution while the latter believed that
the court's verdict denied its due rights in social
administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
