<HEADLINE> Beijing Newspapers Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin said here yesterday that the
cooperation between China and the United States on economic,
trade, science and technology issues has a promising future.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with John Gibbons, assistant to U.S. president
Bill Clinton for science and technology policy, Jiang said the
level of such cooperation is still low in comparison to both
countries' needs for economic growth, and that the potential of
such cooperation is yet to be tapped.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are faced with an "unprecedented opportunity"
to further economic, trade, scientific and technological
cooperation, he said, hoping that both sides will continue efforts
to promote such cooperation, thus benefiting the people of both
countries.
</P>
<P>
-- The mover towards trans-regional, trans-national and
intertrade cooperation and diversified ownership is an inevitable
trend in the development of large enterprise groups in China, said
Premier Li Peng here yesterday at a ceremony marking the
establishment of the Donglian Group.
</P>
<P>
Donglian is a united petro-chemical conglomerate formed by an
unprecedented combination of five large companies in east China's
Jiangsu Province. It has total assets of 50 billion yuan and
workforce of 145,700 people.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin had a wide-ranging and in-depth
exchange of views on Sino-Cuban relations and issues of common
concern yesterday with visiting Raul Castro Ruz, first
vice-president of the Council of State and Council of Ministers of
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said Castro's visit will surely strengthen unity and
co-operation between the two countries and the two Communist
parties and congratulated Raul Castro on the success of the Cuban
Communist Party's Fifth National Congress.
</P>
<P>
Raul Castro said that Cuban people admire the achievements of
the Chinese people in economic progress, and he wants to be better
acquainted with China through the visit.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Qian Qichen, in a report to officials here
yesterday, said that Sino-U.S. relations entered a new phase of
development after President Jiang Zemin's visit to the United
States, but improving and developing bilateral ties is still a
long and complicated process.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The number of cases of HIV/AIDS reported in China had risen
to 8,277 by the end of September, the Ministry of Health disclosed
here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 168 of the patients had AIDS and 77.5 percent were
drug users. From January to September, 2,237 new HIV positive
cases have been found. Based on 1996 figures, it is estimated that
China may already have 150,000 to 200,000 people infected.
</P>
<P>
AIDS in China has entered a third stage since 1994. It started
among the transient population and paid blood donors in central
parts of China, and spread among drug users in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region and Sichuan Province last year.
</P>
<P>
-- Students, teachers or senior citizens -- Chinese or
foreigners -- who want to fly can get up to 40 percent off ticket
prices on China's domestic airlines.
</P>
<P>
Students during their vacations, men over 60, women over 55 and
group travelers may be granted a maximum of 40 percent off the
ticket price.
</P>
<P>
Airlines also will slash air fares for those choosing to fly on
their earliest or last flights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
