<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Demands Safe Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The nation's 135 million
employees of township enterprises are expected to be working in
safer conditions thanks to the government's continuous action
against dangerous production, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
According to Vice-Minister of Agriculture Liu Chengguo, his
ministry and the Ministry of Labour will emphasize safety control
of accident-prone township enterprises as part of the efforts to
ensure the sector's safe production in a three-year campaign.
</P>
<P>
The ministries have targeted township firms in the fields of
mining, fireworks, construction materials and chemical industries,
Liu said at a safe production working conference in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Local governors will be held responsible for any accident
occurring in rural firms, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Although much progress has been made in the area of on-the-job
safety in the past years, accident-prone production is still a
problem.
</P>
<P>
A recent statistics shows that 917 people died in accidents at
rural firms in the first six months of this year, down 19 percent
from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In three years, the special administration of these rural firms
will further cut down accident cases, the vice-minister said.
</P>
<P>
Across the country, more than 23 million township enterprises
in a variety of fields now form the pillar of the rural economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
