<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ski Jumper Goldberger given permission to compete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, November 19 (Xinhua) -- 1996 ski flying world champion
Andreas Goldberger of Austria was on Wednesday free from a
one-year ban and given permission to compete for another country.
</P>
<P>
Goldberger's manager Edi Federer, however, did not disclose
which countries were willing to give Goldberger the licence
required for World Cup events, a news report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said an Austrian court issued the order which will
save Goldberger, twice winner of ski jumping's overall World Cup,
permitting him participating in the November 29-30 World Cup
opener in Lillehammer, Norway.
</P>
<P>
The ban was demanded by the Austrian Ski Federation (OeSV), due
to Goldberger's resignation from the OeSV after it suspended him
from six monthes for having used cocaine and denied him the
liberty of training with his own coach.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with International Ski Federation (FIS) rules, a
national federation is entitled to request a ban when an athlete
chooses to join another federation.
</P>
<P>
OeSV president Peter Schroecksnadel said: "We have to accept
the court's decision but we will contest it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
