<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, November 20 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami has said hat he
has assigned a team to work out a favorable economic system for
the country, local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a TV interview Tuesday night on the occasion of 100 days in
office, Khatami said that the most important task for his
government was to improve the country's economic structure in the
fields of production, consumption and distribution.
(Iran-Khatami-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's newly-appointed Interior Minister Habib al
Adli Wednesday made massive changes in the top posts of his
ministry and the police, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle came as part of efforts to beef up the country's
security system after the horrific slaughter of 58 foreign
tourists on Monday in Luxor, about 500 kilometers south of Cairo.
(Egypt-Police-Reshuffle)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Foreign Minister Amr Moussa has warned Israel not to
thrust itself into the current Iraqi crisis with the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the press Wednesday, Moussa said Israel had
better "steer clear of an issue that does not concern it" and that
any Israeli involvement in the matter would only stymie any
forthcoming solution.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the current U.N.-Iraq standoff over arms
inspection. The U.S. is beefing up its military presence in the
Gulf for a possible strike on Baghdad which has expelled American
U.N. officials in charge of scuttling weapons of mass
destruction. (Egypt-Iraq-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- Ambassador Sha Zukang at China's permanent mission in
Geneva will take part in a ministerial meeting to end the
three-week-old Iraq weapons inspection crisis peacefully,
diplomatic sources said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sha will join British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, French
Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine, Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright for the
meeting expected at about 3 am Geneva time on Thursday in the
Geneva International Airport. (Geneva-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Six people were killed and one wounded when a
South African light aircraft crashed into the sea off Mozambican
coast on Tuesday, the South African Civil Aviation Authorities
(CAA) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
One survivor sustained slight injuries and was flown back to
South Africa where he was admitted to a Johannesburg hospital,
according to a report of the South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
The nationalities of the passengers were not known.
</P>
<P>
CAA Chief Director, Rennie van Zyl, said the aircraft was
initially trapped under about four meters of water near the town
of Vilanculos. (Safrica-Plane Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States would make mistakes if it takes
unilateral military action against Iraq and it would not win any
support from its allies for that,former President Jimmy Carter
said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I think it would be a serious mistake. We would not have the
support from any of our allies if we did that. We would stand
alone if we launched a military attack," Carter told NBC in an
interview. (US-Iraq-Carter)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
