<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian State Duma on Wednesday passed a
resolution requesting President Boris Yeltsin to dismiss the First
Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anatoly Chubais, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also invited the president to send a inquiry to
the Prosecutor General "to obtain information relating to
observation of law by other top government officials."
</P>
<P>
The Duma supported Yeltsin in dismissing top federal executives
"who compromised themselves," the report said.
(Russia-Duma-Minister)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. space shuttle Columbia, carrying a
multinational crew of six on a 16-day science mission, Wednesday
blasted into orbit from the Kennedy Space Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
The 4.5 million-pound spaceship was launched into a hazy sky at
2:46 p.m. EST (1946 GMT), right on the mark, as the clouds turned
out to be not as thick as forecasters had feared.
</P>
<P>
During the long-time orbit journey, Columbia's astronauts will
release a solar observatory and retrieve it two days later,
conduct a practice spacewalk that was canceled last year because
of a stuck hatch, and grow plants and crystals. (US-Shuttle
Columbia-Launch)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada -- The annual Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) forum kicked off here Wednesday with Senior
officials sitting down to prepare ground for the leaders'
conference scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials representing 18 economies on the Pacific Rim
gathered in the Vancouver Trade &AMP; Convention Center this morning
for two-day meeting in preparation for the summit, the fifth since
1993. (Canada-APEC Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- President Bill Clinton said Wednesday that the
United States preferred a peaceful solution to the dispute with
Iraq but on the condition that Iraq fully comply with
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that the United States would take whatever steps
necessary to end the impasse over the weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"I prefer to resolve this situation peacefully with our friends
and allies," Clinton said at a bill signing ceremony at the White
House. (US-Iraq-Arms Inspections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq is concerned with the lastest developments in
Russia's effort to find a way out of the present standoff between
Baghdad and the U.N. without resorting to military operations.
</P>
<P>
The official Iraq News Agency reported Wednesday that President
Saddam Hussein presided over a Cabinet meeting to review efforts
in solving the crisis through diplomatic and political means.
</P>
<P>
The report said Saddam briefed his Cabinet members on the
Russian plan to end the showdown, whose details have never been
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The report did not elaborate on the meeting. (Iraq-Russia-Plan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Six F-117a stealth fighters landed at Langley Air
Force Base in Virginia Wednesday on their way from their base in
New Mexico to Kuwait to join the U.S. air and naval force already
in the Gulf for possible military action on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The F-117a stealth fighters and six B-52 bombers were ordered
to the Gulf by President Bill Clinton Tuesday to beef up American
air and naval forces in the region. (US-Iraq-Stealth Jets) 
</P>
