<HEADLINE> Manila Eyes Precautionary IMF Aid in Case of Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines is considering a "precautionary arrangement with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) after the country exits from the
IMF's 35 years of supervision.
</P>
<P>
Local press today quoted Central Bank governor Gabriel Singson
as saying that the arrangement was discussed in a very preliminary
manner during the meeting of IMF chief Michel Camdessus with
President Fidel Ramos and other economic officials earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
Access to the new arrangement "depends on the country's needs,
just like what we have now," Singson said, referring to the IMF's
existing Extended Fund Facility for the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The bank governor said such an arrangement is necessary because
of the ongoing currency turmoil in the region.
</P>
<P>
"(But as to) the terms of the program: how long, how much will
be the amount involved -- these things have not yet been
discussed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Singson stressed that the arrangement is neither a standby
facility nor an extension of the Extended Fund Facility and is
dependent on the Philippines' graduation from the IMF tutelage by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Regardless of the new arrangement with the IMF, the country
will "have a program of our own to ensure fiscal and monetary
discipline," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
