<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Administration Handles Motions from Deputies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing municipal
government has seriously handled proposals from the deputies of
the Beijing People's Congress to promote the government work.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by Zhu Zupu, deputy secretary-general of the
municipal government, in his report to the 41st session of the
Standing Committee of the 10th Beijing People's Congress
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Shen Mengpei and the other 178 deputies put forward a motion to
develop public transportation and alleviate traffic congestion in
the capital city. Their motion suggested that priority should be
given to public transportation and special lanes be designated for
public buses.
</P>
<P>
The motion prompted the municipal government to give public
transportation a pivotal position. In June, Beijing's first
special lane for public buses was designated on Chang'an Avenue,
one of the busiest streets in the capital.
</P>
<P>
This is just one of the 1,130 motions the deputies have
proposed to the municipal government this year. And the government
has solved 30 percent of the problems the motions covered, Zhu
said.
</P>
<P>
The motions involve various aspects of the capital's
development such as the reform of State enterprises, urban
planning, construction and management as well as science and
education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
