<HEADLINE> Kohl's Coalition Partner Threatened by Funding Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The junior partner of German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's ruling coalition, the Free Democratic
Party (FDP), could be forced to return 12.4 million marks (7.2
million U.S. dollars) it received in state funds in 1996 because
it had failed to follow the application procedures.
</P>
<P>
The FDP received the bad news after a German court ruled
Wednesday evening that the party had received the money wrongly
because it had failed to submit an application for the funds by
the September 30 deadline in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to German press reports, FDP treasurer Hermann Otto
Solms had apparently forgotten to submit the application in time
in 1996. Nevertheless, the party eventually got the money after an
approval by German parliament speaker Rita Suessmuth.
</P>
<P>
Whether the FDP should return the funds would be decided by the
court later.
</P>
<P>
Under German law, political parties are entitled to state funds
in proportion to the number of votes they receive in federal,
regional and European elections.
</P>
<P>
The court's verdict could deal a heavy financial blow to the
FDP, whose votes could be vital for Kohl to win an unprecedented
fifth term in the next German general elections due in September
1998, analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
