<HEADLINE> Vancouver Promotes Business at APEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The city of Vancouver and
Canada as a whole are taking advantage of the APEC meetings here
to promote business and trade.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the meetings where officials are trying to gain
agreement on free-trade initiatives, efforts are being made here
to enhance the images of Canadian products and businesses.
</P>
<P>
Take for example media kits that every journalist gets on his
or her arrival here. In addition to an APEC booklet and some
information about the city and province, there are pamphlets on
the Vancouver Stock Exchange and others, and even a CD or the
Canadian Exporters Catalogue.
</P>
<P>
If you want to import Canadian products, you are sure to get
enough information of Canadian companies, and that's good for the
sale of Canadian goods and services.
</P>
<P>
Private companies are actively participating in the event, by
contributing either money or services to the event.
</P>
<P>
In return, these companies' logos will be displayed prominently
where major events are unfolded, and information about them will
be disseminated to the media.
</P>
<P>
And the provincial and municipal governments here are trying
their best to capitalize on the week-long event here, which starts
today.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government of British Columbia (B.C.) has set up
a media information center of its own as part of the major
international media center. It provides almost all information
about the province, its economy, investment policies and major
companies.
</P>
<P>
B.C. Premier Glen Clark came and opened the center this morning
amidst the limelight of local and international media.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest immediate impact is going to be 500 million people
around the world watching Vancouver, looking at what we have to
offer," Clark said.
</P>
<P>
"The benefit here is to elevate Vancouver as the gateway to
North America from Asia, and the gateway from North America to
Asia... and elevate B.C. as the Canadian province on the Pacific
Rim," Clark noted.
</P>
<P>
To promote business and trade, the province also set up the
B.C. Business Crossroads Center, a showcase of B.C. businesses and
new technologies.
</P>
<P>
It's nothing strange that B.C. attaches such great importance
to the APEC event, considering the fact that its exports to APEC
member economies top 2.5 million dollars every hour.
</P>
<P>
Having the APEC meeting in Vancouver is "like having 18 of your
best customers pay you a visit," Premier Clark noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
