<HEADLINE> Blair Calls on Parties to Name Major Donors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Tony Blair today
called on all parties in the country to name their major donors
over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
He told parliament he had proposed that all parties should give
details of donations above 5,000 pounds (8,500 U.S. dollars)
received since the 1992 general election to a committee looking
into party political funding.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that (committee chairman) Sir Patrick Neill be
able to look at all the donations -- both the amounts and the
donors -- that have been made going back to 1992," the prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Blair's Labor government has been trying to calm a row over a
million pound (1.7 million dollar) political donation by chief of
Formula One Bernie Ecclestone before the May 1 election which
swept the Labor party to power.
</P>
<P>
But the move came too late to spare one of his ministers a
grilling over why the Labor government had scrapped banning
tobacco sponsorship of Formula One motor racing.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government came under heavy fire from newspapers
and political opponents over the donation and its relaxation of
policy on tobacco advertising.
</P>
<P>
The government acknowledged it had received the 1 million pound
donation but disassociated the donation with the relaxation of
tobacco ban on Formula One. Labor officials also promised to
return the donation very soon.
</P>
<P>
Peter Mandelson, minister in charge of policy presentation,
earlier admitted the government could not be proud of the way it
had handled the row, releasing details of Ecclestone's donation
only slowly and defensively.
</P>
<P>
"The government behaved out of character. We acted against our
own principles -- that honesty is the first principle of good
government," Mandelson told a conference of government
communication managers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
