<HEADLINE> US Dollar Nears 5-Year High Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar almost
reached a 5-year high against the Japanese yen today after Japan's
prime minister said the country would not use public funds to
support its banking system.
</P>
<P>
The yen fell sharply and the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index
suffered its biggest one-day point drop this year after Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said he did not support the use of
public funds to help ailing banks.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's ascent against the yen also was aided by further
economic troubles in South Korea, where the won currency hit a
record low against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The dollar peaked during the day at 127.42 yen -- above a
5-year high of 127.14 reached on April 10, 1992 -- but retreated to
settle in late New York trading at 127.00, up from 126.15 late
Tuesday. The dollar has not finished higher since April 30, when
it hit 127.06.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also moved against the German mark as U.S. blue-chip
stocks rose higher. The U.S. currency was quoted at 1.7318 marks,
up from 1.7294.
</P>
<P>
The new Taiwan dollar also hit a record low against the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday:
1.4034 Swiss francs, down from 1.4053; 5.7955 French francs, up
from 5.7910; 1,696 Italian lire, up from 1,693; and 1.4156 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.4140.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6912 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6909 U.S. dollars. 
