<HEADLINE> Annan: TV Power Should Be Partner in Pursuit of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The power of television
should be a partner in pursuit of a better future, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan stressed here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the second United Nations World Television Forum,
Annan said at this event, "we will open channels of closer
collaboration between regions and cultures. In doing so, we will
help to promote greater understanding and tolerance among
nations."
</P>
<P>
Annan said, "We now are living in an interdependent, global
village and facing new realities. We must accept change as an
essential condition of life." The challenge facing mankind today
cut across all borders and they involved all aspects of human
security, but human understanding had not yet grasped them, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said issues before the United Nations,
such as the environment, drugs, pandemics, and sustainable
development, were issues carrying no passports. "This is the
message we are trying to send to the world," he said, adding that
the public was still thinking in local terms.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said, "Information has a great democratizing power
waiting to be harnessed to our global struggle for peace and
development." It was ignorance, not knowledge, that made enemies
of men. It was ignorance, not knowledge, that made fighters of
children.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the quantity and quality of available information
was changing dramatically every day, in every country and in every
corner of the world. Citizens were gaining greater access to
information.
</P>
<P>
He said the challenge now was to make information available to
all. For too long, economic inequality had prevented the large
majority of men and women on this planet from taking advantage of
the bounty of knowledge. The United Nations was now working to
develop with television a relationship of openness and mutual
trust.
</P>
<P>
He stressed with the help of television, the world could be
brought alive, and "we can help ensure our young are the first to
benefit from this knowledge, and to make it their partner in the
pursuit of a better future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
