<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The British government is
considering withdrawing several hundred troops from Northern
Ireland in the next few weeks, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
"It is being actively considered at the moment. A decision may
be made by the end of the week," Reuters quoted a military source
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Britain has some 17,000 troops in Northern Ireland and the
source said that the number to be pulled out would probably be
around 500.
</P>
<P>
An uneasy peace has been maintained in the divided province of
Northern Ireland since July when the Irish Republican Army (IRA)
called a ceasefire in its 28-year struggle against British rule.
</P>
<P>
A dozen senior officials of the IRA recently quit the political
wing Sinn Fein in protest against new peace policies aimed at a
political settlement through talks, leaving the truce in danger.
</P>
<P>
Britain says that the IRA's ceasefire is intact, but police
officers were last week put on alert in case of attacks by
republican dissidents. 
