<HEADLINE> Clinton: Iraq Must Comply With UN Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
today that the United States preferred a peaceful solution to the
dispute with Iraq but on the condition that Iraq fully comply with
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that the United States would take whatever steps
necessary to end the impasse over the weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"I prefer to resolve this situation peacefully with our friends
and allies," Clinton said at a bill signing ceremony at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
But "Iraq must comply with the unanimous will of the
international community and let the weapons inspectors resume
their work to prevent Iraq from developing an arsenal of nuclear,
chemical and biological weapons," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were made before the five permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council hold an emergency meeting in Geneva on the
Iraq crisis and were deemed as showing the American staunch
position in defusing the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"That's our top line, that's our bottom line," Clinton said. "I
want to achieve it diplomatically. But we're taking every step to
make sure we are prepared to pursue whatever options are
necessary."
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Clinton ordered dispatch of six B-52 bombers and
six F-117 stealth fighters to the Gulf to beef up American
military presence in the region. He also authorized the commander
of U.S. forces in the Gulf to organize an air expeditionary force
with 30 fighters and B-1 bombers. 
