<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-19 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: U.S. Open for All Options in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 19 (Xinhua) -- The United States wants a
peaceful solution to end its standoff with Iraq over arms
inspections but it is open to other options, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said here today.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who cut short her visit to India for an unannounced
visit to Egypt tonight, made the statement after a meeting with
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa at the Cairo Airport.
</P>
<P>
She said that the persistent and ultimate aim of Washington
since the crisis started is a resumption of inspections by
U.N. arms experts.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that Iraq should comply with the will of the
international community and must allow the U.N. arms inspectors
back to Baghdad to continue their job.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Baghdad must destroy its chemical and biological
weapons that pose a threat the world without any precondition, she
added.
</P>
<P>
U.N. arms inspectors pulled out of Iraq following Iraq's order
on October 29 expelling Americans working in the U.N. Commission
on dismantling its weapons of mass destruction. The U.S.,
encouraging a harsher economic sanctions on Baghdad, has threatened
military strikes to settle the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. diplomat said she will fly from Cairo to Geneva for a
pre-dawn meeting Thursday with the foreign ministers of Russia,
France and Britain to discuss the Iraqi-U.N. standoff.
</P>
<P>
She will get acquainted with the outcome of the contacts Moscow
held with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz and expound the
U.S. measures and stand on the issue sparked off by Iraqi failure
to comply with the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The hastily arranged meeting follows efforts by Russia to ease
the crisis over U.N. weapons inspections as Washington has decided
to beef up its military presence in the Gulf for a possible strike
against Baghdad following the 22-day-old U.N.-Iraq standoff.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Aziz, currently visiting Moscow, will come to Cairo
to meet with Moussa and Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel
Meguid tomorrow to explain Iraq's views on the recent tension
between Iraq and the U.N..
</P>
<P>
He reportedly has devised a proposal with Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeniv Primakov to avert a military confrontation with
the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has sent two messages to Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein, urging him to comply with the U.N.
resolutions and restraining from military showdown with the U.S..
</P>
</TEXT>
