<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Adoption Overhaul Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today signed legislation to speed up moving children from foster
care to "permanent and loving homes."
</P>
<P>
The legislation, approved last week by Congress, is considered
to be the most sweeping set of revisions in nearly two decades to
the nation's adoption and foster care system.
</P>
<P>
At a White House ceremony Clinton said, "The new law will help
us to speed children out of foster care into permanent families by
setting meaningful time limits for child welfare decisions, by
clarifying which family situations call for reasonable
reunification efforts and which simply do not."
</P>
<P>
The measure would emphasize the health and safety of children
over the reunification of families, the current priority.
</P>
<P>
It reduces from 18 months to one year the deadline for states
to find a permanent home for a child. It also terminates parental
rights to children who have been in foster homes 15 of the
previous 22 months. Courts will be required to cut off parental
rights almost immediately if there is evidence of abandonment or
severe abuse.
</P>
<P>
At present, children who have been removed from their natural
families and cannot safely return to them typically wait three
years or more to be placed in permanent homes.
</P>
<P>
The new law provides cash bonuses of 4,000 to 6,000 dollars per
child for states that increase adoptions.
</P>
<P>
The number of children in foster care has grown 89 percent
since 1982. But the average number of children adopted from foster
care has held steady at about 20,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
Child welfare advocates generally welcome the legislation but
insist that more action is necessary for the half-million U.S.
children in foster care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
