<DOCNO> XIE19971120.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Prefers Peaceful Solution to Dispute with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 19 (Xinhua) -- U. S. President Bill
Clinton said on Wednesday that the United States preferred a
peaceful solution to the dispute with Iraq but on the condition
that Iraq fully comply with U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
But He also said that the United States would take whatever
steps necessary to end the impasse over the weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"I prefer to resolve this situation peacefully with our friends
and allies," Clinton said at a bill signing ceremony at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
But "Iraq must comply with the unanimous will of the
international community and let the weapons inspectors resume
their work to prevent Iraq from developing an arsenal of nuclear,
chemical and biological weapons," He said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks before five permanent members of U.N.
Security Council hold an emergency meeting in Geneva on the Iraqi
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"That's our top line, that's our bottom line," Clinton said. "I
want to achieve it diplomatically. But we are taking every step to
make sure we are prepared to pursue whatever options are
necessary."
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Clinton ordered dispatch of six B-52 bombers and
six F-117 stealth fighters to the Persian Gulf region to beef up
American military presence in the region. He also authorized the
commander of U.S. forces in the Gulf to organize an air
expeditionary force with 30 fighters and B-1 bombers.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov have had talks over the past two days with Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz on how to solve the present weapons
inspection dispute. The result was their proposal to hold an
emergency meeting in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Russia said it had worked out a blueprint for the settlement of
the dispute, which will be presented at the Geneva meeting.
</P>
<P>
But the United States was cautious about the talks in Geneva
among five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"We will be looking carefully to see if the requirements of the
Security Council have been met," White House Spokesman Mike
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
He repeated Clinton's remarks, saying "Our preference is to
resolve this matter peacefully, but it has to be resolved
consistent with the strong presentations that have been made by
the U.N. Security Council." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
